properties.nom_etablissement: YUAN YUAN DESIGN STUDIO, Silence, Shanghai, Chine
properties.description_projet: Silence' is an installation, an exploration of food waste and natural dyes. This creation combines modern technologies, traditional craftsmanship, and various artistic techniques to poetically integrate the ever-changing qualities of food into everyday object design.

properties.nom_etablissement: ULTRACONFIDENTIEL DESIGN, Amazon Blink - Fashion Studio, Gurgaon, India
properties.description_projet: Amazon BLINK - Fashion Studio - Gurgaon - 44,000 Sft. Ultraconfidentiel Design has designed the fashion studio for Amazon BLINK, located in New Delhi, India. This was a very unique project earlier harbouring New York and London, Amazon gave us the opportunity to conceptualize the first of its kind Amazon Fashion Studio in India. Designed to boost creativity and interactions between all generations of fashion designers, BLINK studio’s energy is fully enhanced thought open spaces and collaborative areas. The subtle blend of modern designs and revisited Indian traditions inhabits this studio and gives its uniqueness. All along the place, details have been thought by Ultraconfidentiel’s Design team to tell a story and depict not only fashion but also the essence of India. For this studio, one of the requirements was to bring some Indian touches though the space to create its identity for instance, we decided to focus on phone booths to show the cultural diversity of India though fabrics specific to different regions. The use of modern version of Mughal Jaalis specially invented and customized for this project, and faded-red color micro-concrete flooring to remind the sandstone used in architecture through the Indian sub-continent. The design expectations were set high. It was a challenging project given by its nature and also the fact that it was our first assignment for a Fashion Studio. A lot of technical aspects were involved which made the project more enticing. This Studio spans across 44,000 Sq. Ft. in Vipul Agora, Gurgaon and has over 14 on-Body bays, a merchandise coordination area, complete with production room, editorial bay, a large office space and operations area. The premise can also un-fold itself for large gathering and corporate meets. The rustic and industrial look with subtle glimpse of Indian fashion, textile and elements completes the individuality of fashion and creates its own unique style.

properties.nom_etablissement: VIEWPORT STUDIO, Wales Millenium Centre, Bute Pl, Cardiff CF10 5AL, United Kingdom
properties.adresse: Bute Pl, Cardiff CF10 5AL, United Kingdom
properties.description_projet: Wales Millennium Centre commissioned us to design the first major refurbishment of the centre since opening in 2004. We have crafted five new front-of-house spaces. The central Welcome Space incorporates a bar, bistro, co-working and meeting areas. A private Members Lounge is situated on the first floor. The South Atrium leads to a 140-seat Cabaret, via retail, food and beverage spaces.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, Merdeka Textile Museum , Kuala Lumpur, Malaysia
properties.description_projet: The overarching ambition for the new Merdeka Textile Museum is to become an inclusive cultural institution for Everyone, from Novice to Expert. Guiding the design articulation is the focus on the look and feel which will communicate a coherent visitor journey through the 8 collection themes. 6 distinctive design elements were identified and explored to provide tangibility in “Look” and “Feel”. They assisted in strengthening the framework led by “Bunga Pecah Lapan” (a motif found in traditional Malay textiles) and “Drape, Wrap, Fold”. The juxtaposition of these elements proposes a sense of grandeur and dynamism that is subtle yet impactful, inviting yet exquisite. Combined, they exuberate a universal language by involving the engagement of the 5 human senses, fitting for the inclusive museum journey through the long-standing heritage of Malayan textiles.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, St James Power Station Heritage Trail And Gallery , Singapore, Singapore
properties.titre_affiche: St James Power Station Heritage Trail And Gallery
properties.description_projet: St James Power Station, a glorious industrial power house of Singapore is now a notable heritage icon in Singapore and a successful example of adaptive reuse. It is important to pay homage to the historical architecture while integrating the heritage trail and gallery with a renewed landscape and interior of the Dyson office. The design direction of the gallery aims to showcase the value of heritage through the legacy of its materials and artefacts. Moving towards the future, it is pivotal to give the heritage a new lustre and patina. The use of corten steel for the outdoor interpretive panels is reminiscent of the distinctive red brick façade. New materials such as steel beams and granites are the site’s material palette. The interior design of the upper-level floor slabs in the Dyson office made use of layered wood and white painted finishes, which inspired the principle of cohesively layering and overlapping various materials in the indoor gallery. The L-wall of the gallery features a niche wall with various elements which curate visitor journeys into one that has layers of discovery and exploration. The design intent is to craft a coherent visitor journey of discovery with clear navigation by connecting various themes through a simple and timeless spatial approach. Our evidence-based approach to design defines the design language to allow the new elements to merge with existing fabric, ensuring that the historical artefacts take precedence throughout the heritage trail.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, Good Design Research Pop-up Exhibition , Singapore, Singapore
properties.description_projet: The Good Design Research Pop-up Exhibition is conceptualized to bring design closer to the everyday man. Translated through the design of 3 mega coves, the curatorial theme “A Day in The Life” synergizes to house a curated set of prototypes and research. The exhibition design colour scheme – Green, Orange, and Purple, shape the visitor’s journey through daily ticks of the clock: Morning, Afternoon, and Night. The curved niches were further developed to translate designs empowering nature in impacting our day-to-day activities. Sustainably constructed in standard-sized plywood and recycled steel structures, these free-standing inward panels were strategically placed. They assisted in dynamically opening up multiple vistas for content glimpses of exploration in the open space while doubling up to create focused display views for the permanent shops behind. Overhangs were the final design touch in ensuring the temporary outdoor exhibition remains immersive next to the busy road. They function to diffuse traffic noise at peak hours of the day while communicating through form design’s impact in resolving challenges.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, Gallery Children's Biennale 2023: Let's Make A Better Place , Singapore, Singapore
properties.titre_affiche: Gallery Children's Biennale 2023: Let's Make A Better Place
properties.description_projet: The Gallery Children’s Biennale has been a key programme of National Gallery Singapore since 2017, embodying the Gallery’s commitment to inspiring young, curious minds with art. It aims to explore the many ways that children can learn and play while also engaging more with the world around them. This year, the Biennale features 11 interactive and immersive artworks responding to the theme of “Let’s Make A Better Place,” inviting children and adults to discover how we can create a world built upon this year’s core values of care, respect, imagination and collaboration. Ten artists from Singapore and beyond conceived new artworks for the Biennale. These artists are: Arahmaiani (Indonesia), Chiang Yu Xiang (Singapore), International Museum of Children’s Art (Norway), Fadilah Karim (Malaysia), LittleCr3atures® x Jevon Chandra x Lynette Quek (Singapore), Tawatchai Puntusawasdi (Thailand), Izziyana Suhaimi (Singapore), Wang Ruobing (Singapore), Kumi Yamashita (Japan/USA), and Ly Yeow (Singapore). Centred on art created for, with, and by children, the Biennale is a warm and welcoming space for everyone to have conversations about their dreams, ideas, and even struggles. This edition also includes both digital and on-site programmes that will inspire visitors of all ages.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, Gallery Children's Biennale 2021: Why Art Matters , Singapore, Singapore
properties.titre_affiche: Gallery Children's Biennale 2021: Why Art Matters
properties.description_projet: The Gallery Children’s Biennale is a space for self-expression and creative exploration, empowering children with a renewed sense of empathy and confidence to engage with the ever-changing world around them while embracing the shared values of acceptance, openness and diversity. This year, nine artists from Singapore and Southeast Asia were asked to address the theme, “Why Art Matters”. Faced with the emergence of the Covid-19 pandemic, the gallery had to re-think the notion of engagement. In response, the artists were invited to conceive artworks as both online and on-site interactive works and physical installations. With a range of programmes for children and families, the Gallery Children’s Biennale aim to inspire young minds with artistic experiences that can transform a child’s understanding of the world around them, and what is creatively possible.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, World Cities Summit Pavilion , Singapore, Singapore
properties.description_projet: The World Cities Summit Pavilion is the highlight of the visitor’s experience, branding itself as an exemplary architectural feature that is structurally environmentally friendly, recyclable, and visually aesthetical in reflecting the World Cities Summit theme/ narrative. Venturing into nature’s backyard to develop the biophilic design of “The Blooming Garden”, which guides the Singapore Pavilion’s form, spatial transitions and the relationship between interacting elements to cohesively map a visitor’s journey. The Singapore Pavilion’s design language is inspired by the way plant cells multiply. Its resiliency, restorative and regenerative processes greatly align with the World Cities Summit’s theme and purpose, as well as the Centre for Liveable Cities’ mission – to distil, create and share knowledge on liveable and sustainable cities. Individual interlocking stacks, varying in scale, draw parallels to the agencies’ diversity, united by a common goal to advance upwards.

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO ARCHITECTS, Museums of Royal Kingdoms of India & Gujarat, Kevadia, Gujart, India
properties.titre_affiche: Museums of Royal Kingdoms of India & Gujarat
properties.description_projet: Our design creates a world-class cultural destination, that celebrates the rich history and evolution of India while accenting the importance of the Gujarat region in that story. The museum complex will be an enriching experience that will delight, educate and inspire visitors, instilling a sense of pride for generations to come. The Museum Complex is located on a commanding site overlooking the Narmada River. The river is central to a developing tourist district whose focus is the Statue of Unity, the largest statue in the world and a significant landmark for visitors. The new complex acts as a cultural gateway for the pilgrimage to the statue. It is visible from the Ekta entry to the district, from across the river, thereby attracting visitors and is directly accessed via the New Gora Bridge. The site is dramatic and inspiring in consideration of the surrounding context. Designing the masterplan according to the surrounding site context, in consideration of how MORKI and GVM correspond to the entirety of master planning.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO MHNA, Swiss Chocolate by Fassbind, Zähringerstrasse 46, 8001 Zürich, Switzerland
properties.description_projet: Here is a gourmet hotel... a tribute to the famous Swiss chocolate. It is a new concept for Swiss Hotels by Fassbind, in line with those that Studio MHNA has developed for same client at other times, notably around wine (Swiss Wine in Lausanne), and others around mountain pastures (Swiss Night in Zurich and Lausanne). From the hotel entrance, through the reception/breakfast area, the corridors and into the rooms, the story tells the chocolate's one and in particular its manufacture and transformation in Switzerland, making it famous throughout the world. The chocolate colour tones are used throughout the project, and there are many harmonies and nods to the theme.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO MHNA, Mövenpick Hotel, Avenue Terrasson De Fougeres Angle, Rue Gourgas, Abidjan, Côte d’Ivoire
properties.adresse: Avenue Terrasson De Fougeres Angle, Rue Gourgas, Abidjan, Côte d’Ivoire
properties.description_projet: In the heart of Abidjan's business district, Studio MHNA has signed the latest project for the Mövenpick hotel group in Ivory Coast. Numerous works by contemporary African artists are incorporated into the interior architecture proposed by Studio MHNA. It is a real tribute to Africa as a whole, with the choices of local materials, ethnic decorative patterns, works of art and forms. To counterbalance these colourful atmospheres, the 160 rooms have been designed in an urban spirit with shades of grey. Within this aesthetic framework that leaves nothing to chance, the Mövenpick Hotel Abidjan reinforces the dynamism of the hotel offer in the Ivorian capital while relying on the artistic inclination of the venue, wished by the owner and implemented by Studio MHNA.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO MHNA, Club Med Magna Marbella, C. Padre Paco Ostos, S/N, 29601 Trapiche, Málaga, Spain
properties.adresse: C. Padre Paco Ostos, S/N, 29601 Trapiche, Málaga, Spain
properties.description_projet: In the heart of Andalusia, Studio MHNA has designed the new Club Med Magna Marbella, bringing the Andalusian soul and its cultural mix to every corner of the 4-trident resort. Its eclectic and colourful style resonates with the history of this Spanish land of character. For this new collaboration with the Club Med group, the tandem formed by Marc Hertrich and Nicolas Adnet expresses the originality and boldness of their colourful style on a grand scale. The richness of the forms, the motifs and the artistic references give this village a powerful aesthetic.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO MVW & EDITION DE VIE, The Camus Cognac Gallery Boutique, District de Xiuying, Haikou, Haïnan, Chine
properties.adresse: District de Xiuying, Haikou, Haïnan, Chine
properties.description_projet: “Beauty and refinement” • Convey the passion of a French family, continually dedicated to the making of high quality, distinctive cognacs. • Solution providing functional retail and gallery space, and high-end guest bar and lounge facilities • Spatial retail experiences and finishes in a way that stokes the relation between earth and sky – and evokes the dynamism and poetry of drinking a glass of prestigious Camus cognac • Space divided into different zones to create separate zones with Camus’ Cognacs environment inspiration, with a contemporary and vitality twist • Warm interior spaces embrace a uniquely Camus Cognac palette of materials, textures and colors, designed to represent the history and elegance of the French brand • Inspiration form organic environment of Cognac into the interior design development • Integration of iconic signature landmark such as logo of Camus Cognac : the pinnacle feature of this area within the selling space is the majestic chandelier composed of different layers of lighting and forming multiples logos of the brand beautifully lit from above and reflected in infinity into the mirrored ceiling. • Immersive experiences with “instagrammable” moments from the façade to the store and gallery.

properties.nom_etablissement: SYBILLE DE MARGERIE, Private Ranch, Aspen, Colorado, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: Aspen is a renowned ski resort located in the Rocky Mountains of Colorado. Originally a center for silver mine operations, Aspen has gradually transformed into a world-famous destination for winter sports. Many affluent individuals from the United States and around the globe own properties in this prestigious ski area, captivated by its exceptional natural surroundings. During the heart of winter, when the cold and snow envelop the area, the ranch offers a serene and tranquil atmosphere with its golden woods resembling the bark of aspen trees. Its curved shapes and use of natural materials evoke a sense of delicacy and sophistication. Aspen boasts an extraordinary ski area characterized by speed, skillful maneuvers, and visually striking traces left in the snow, reflecting the impeccably designed architecture of the ranch. The interplay between the interior and exterior spaces creates a contrast of blinding light and soothing shadows. Throughout each season, the omnipresent nature showcases the freshness of the undergrowth and the vibrant pastel hues of spring in Aspen, setting the ambiance for the spa and swimming pool at the ranch, which serve as true havens of peace and well-being. After an active day in the hills, one can return to a cozy and comfortable atmosphere, ideal for gathering with family and friends. Soft textures such as velvet and fur, along with gentle lighting and a sensual color palette, contribute to the inviting ambiance. The ranch combines the brilliance of the rising sun on the Rocky Mountains with the serene and welcoming atmosphere of its interior and outdoor spaces. It embodies a Zen attitude, promoting a relaxed, laid-back, and undeniably contemporary lifestyle. Functioning as a protective setting and a luxurious cocoon, the ranch pays homage to skilled artisans who enhance the interior with exquisite details crafted from noble materials such as metal, leather, stone, and wood. The ranch harmoniously blends masculine and feminine elements, just as it integrates with nature's splendid beauty. It showcases a fusion of meticulously planned design pieces and carefully considered couture touches, scattered throughout spaces bathed in a soothing and poetic light.

properties.nom_etablissement: THOMAS DARIEL, LIQUID, Shanghai, Chine
properties.description_projet: LIQUID offices in Shanghai The latest office project designed by Dariel Studio is located in the downtown of Shanghai. Thomas Dariel, founder and leading designer of Dariel Studio, has been designated to work on the entire space, transforming the original space which boosts brilliant sunshine and an outstanding city perspective, into a stylish, simple, yet comfortable and cosy working space for Liquid Group, an integrated advertising agency. The design of this office is inspired by the concept of Biomimicry, which is the design and production of materials, systems and technologies based on the solutions that the natural world adopts. In this case, the designer is inspired by “Roots”, “Fungi”, “Coral”, “Succulents”, and interprets their natural systems with design language, to represent the infinite evolution of creativity. In accordance to the flow, the designer naturally arranged this floor of 1200 sqm into 4 main sections, including 4 working hubs, 1 reception, 8 meeting rooms, 1 townhall and 1 pantry. Widely used wood and white tone, the designer chose low saturation colours to distinguish the sections, and dotted the space with delightful colours to bring out the natural touch of the design. The designer also skillfully paired wood and metal together to boosts the dynamism, also to reduce the weighty sensation and create more space to breathe.

properties.nom_etablissement: THOMAS DARIEL, Art Deco Villa , Fuzhou, Fujian, Chine
properties.description_projet: Art Deco Villa designed by Thomas Dariel for Dariel Studio, in Fuzhou in China. 860 m2 over three floors with all the furnitures designed by Thomas Dariel or vintage.

properties.nom_etablissement: TRISTAN AUER, Amman , Amman, Jordanie
properties.description_projet: Renovation of a 1600m2 house in Amman, home for a family of 5 and designed to receive a lot (dinners for 40) and on a daily basis, especially indoor in one of the 4 living rooms , bar, wine cellar, dining room and winter garden, or in the outdoor lounges and belvédère, around the pool bar. The Jordanian craftsmen excelled in the marble laying and the special coatings application worked to measure with the agency, as well as for the wood work. Each space has been thought of as a project in its own, due to the size of the rooms and clients and Tristan’s desire to create tailor-made places, in which the clients recognize themselves and take pleasure in spending time there.

properties.nom_etablissement: ULTRACONFIDENTIEL DESIGN, Mankind Pharma Limited, A Class Apart, Okhla Phase III, Okhla Industrial Estate, New Delhi, Delhi 110020, Inde
properties.titre_affiche: Mankind Pharma Limited, A Class Apart
properties.adresse: Okhla Phase III, Okhla Industrial Estate, New Delhi, Delhi 110020, Inde
properties.description_projet: Mankind Pharma is one of India’s leading and fast-growing pharmaceutical companies. Their new Head Office at New Delhi is situated right in the heart of Okhla Phase III which is the hub of industrial and commercial activity. Spread over seven floors the new company headquarters has been designed as a state-of-the-art corporate office space. Ultraconfidentiel Design was commissioned to develop 125 000 Sq. Ft. of office space for the company’s employees across various hierarchies. The idea was to seamlessly carve-out spaces for the various brand divisions of the company, common areas for gatherings, collaborative working and spaces to relax and rejuvenate. The office draws inspiration from the progressive nature of the company and develops a clean and healthy workspace that favours growth and productivity based on its ethos. The consequent design is a sublime space wrapped in a white canvas, carved-out from large volumes and voids while maximizing the use of natural light. The dynamic office design propels the company’s work culture into a modern territory of future-proof workspaces. The site finds itself amidst a lush green neighbourhood. The built form allows for a great view as well as an ample amount of natural light, the effect of which is maximized by the expansive use of white marble. The marble-clad walls of the triple-height atrium at the front entrance instil a sense of tranquillity and act as a buffer between the outside and inside. Juxtaposed to the white canvas is a hand-beaten brass reception table that forms the foreground of an open courtyard laden with trees and shrubs. A well-designed space has the capacity to affect human behaviour. The open-plan workspaces are strategically placed in order to maximize productivity and longevity of the workspace without compromising the privacy of the work profile. Utmost care has been taken to keep the functional and technical aspects as the primary driving factors for the design. The design promotes the concepts of teamwork and collaboration, thus intermittent spaces for collaborative working and relaxation can be found throughout the various floors of the office. A carefully chosen palette of materials on one hand infuses an element of luxury and on the other ensures high performance and longevity of the workspace. The use of brass accents was a crucial design decision and as a result, the metal can be seen taking the form of a suspended mobile in the triple-height waiting lounge, as do the customised light fixtures and the see-through partition screens across the office space. The office space makes use of smart technology to facilitate smooth operations across the extensive built-up area. Interactive digital screens in the guest area assist users with information about the company. Solutions like access-controlled cabins, sensor-based lighting and wireless chargers integrated within the workstations make for a future-ready modern workspace. Workspaces of tomorrow need to be flexible and adaptive to the rapidly changing trends of the corporate ecosystem. The new Mankind Head Office excels in doing so with its adaptive, mobility-oriented and high-performance workspaces that can be reconfigured to the needs of a growing company and transform themselves to host a variety of uses in years to come.

properties.nom_etablissement: ULTRACONFIDENTIEL DESIGN, Monin Studio, Dhan Mill Compound, Chattarpur, New Delhi, India
properties.adresse: Dhan Mill Compound, Chattarpur, New Delhi, India
properties.description_projet: Ultraconfidentiel completed the new MONIN Studio in “The Dhan Mill” Chattarpur, New Delhi. A new B2B engaging experience for the French-syrup’s lovers. Overview “MONIN is more than a drinks solution, it’s a way of living... a genuine brand experience based on our centenary brand values. It’s about giving pleasure and enjoyment by using only the best natural ingredients in the most exciting and creative way. It’s about authentic taste sensations and consistently high-quality, first-rate consumer experiences, achieved with a respect for our environment”. Ultraconfidentiel was asked to translate the essence of MONIN into a new physical space where customers and people can meet, learn and engage with the brand. A dynamic space with lounges, live bar, private client spaces and a small office space with dedicated meeting rooms create a vibrant environment for the Monin experience. The studio is designed as a fluid and connected space with two open levels. A central “green spine” facing the different areas, widely opened to the mezzanine-floor, providing a fresh connection to nature. The central biophilic island is a composition of indoor plants and herbs which can be picked by the visitors and used for the beverage tasting experience with expert Beverage Innovators in the customer lounge and bar zone. This is a new and engaging way to involve the customer in the beverage preparation while walking the space surrounded by the company legacy timeline and material textures inspired by the French city where MONIN has been founded and still deeply rooted: Bourges. Bourges is everywhere, in every small detail. The brick finish at the studio was inspired from the first MONIN factory and the medieval wooden walls at MONIN studio are inspired by the old architectures of the French city-centre. The new MONIN Studio is a contemporary physical experience following the vision and purpose of the famous French Beverage Innovation and solutions Company.

properties.nom_etablissement: PIERRE-YVES ROCHON, Waldorf Astoria, Damsa Boulevard - Entertainment City, Lusail, Qatar
properties.adresse: Damsa Boulevard - Entertainment City, Lusail, Qatar
properties.description_projet: Global interior design studio Pierre-Yves Rochon (PYR) was tasked with the ground-up build of the public areas, guest rooms and suites, villas, apartments and ESPA Life spa of the newly built Waldorf Astoria Lusail Doha. When approaching this project, Pierre-Yves Rochon (PYR) set out to honor the region's architecture while following the property's criteria and brand guidelines. The hotel boasts 429 guest rooms, suites, and 1-, 2-, and 3-bedroom serviced apartments overlooking 650 feet of private beach and public spaces. This exquisite place of rest and rejuvenation – inspired by a stunning view whose only boundaries are the limits of imagination. PYR took inspiration from natural elements- reflections of water, trees, breezes and billowing sails and tents, changing colors from the ocean - found in nature to create relaxed yet refined, modern spaces all while honoring the heritage of the region. Three major aspects taken into consideration for the design were the location in Doha, being at the seaside, and the building's contemporary architecture. The breathtaking view over the sea is the hotel's highlight and naturally became the focus. PYR brought colors seen in nature inside the hotel, while also using the art in the fabrics and patterns found throughout the Middle East all around the property. Throughout the public areas and guest rooms, the design emulates the grandeur of a modern-day palace, while invoking a sense of comfort for guests. PYR ensured there was a fundamental link between the two areas of the hotel, weaving similar colors and materials such as blue, white, and beige, the wood’s tints, walnut or mahogany, and even similar fabrics featured in the lobby. The lobby allows guests to feel as if they are already out at sea and in nature before they have even stepped outside. The space features full windows with a sea view surrounded by a monumental carpet with an Arabic motif and a ceiling filled with peacock references. In the many rooms, suites, villas and apartments contemporary lines are graceful and fluid, surfaces are rich, embellished with color, pattern and handcrafted detail. Persian rugs, tapestries and upholstered walls exude plush coziness throughout the guest rooms, suites, and villas. Curved corners, walls and vestibules soften circulation and envelop guests as if in a fine boat to invoke the feeling of the rounded bays of Qatar’s long coastline. Design details acknowledge Doha as a multidimensional city of culture and history, a cosmopolitan icon rising from old world tradition. Sleek mashrabiya-inspired screening elements balance openness with privacy, and light with shadow. Modern interpretations of regional patterns, latticework and calligraphy are discovered in textiles, artwork and accessories are featured throughout every space, constantly acknowledging the culture of the region while embracing modernity. The ESPA Life, located in a prime position within the hotel, is the flagship ESPA Life in the Middle East, delivering the ultimate wellness and spa experience. ESPA Life has a stunning 180-degree vista capturing both the bay view and Lusail skyline. Interiors are inspired by the natural landscape of Qatar, with finishes alluding the spirit of the desert sand and shimmering seas by day and night reflecting a true sense of place and a life of luxury. The ESPA Life stands out as a destination for guests to unwind and relax, as well as locals looking for luxurious experiences. While the surrounding city, seas and landscapes are constantly moving and never the same, the Waldorf Astoria Lusail Doha is a steadfast icon of comfort, rest and rejuvenation - a place where one can always return home.

properties.nom_etablissement: RDAI, Bountiful Journey Tower, No. 118, Songjiang Rd, Zhongshan District, Taipei City, Taïwan 10491
properties.adresse: No. 118, Songjiang Rd, Zhongshan District, Taipei City, Taïwan 10491
properties.description_projet: The Bountiful Journey tower is a project for which RDAI designed both the architecture and the interiors, reception and resident lobby lounges, appartments and wellness/relaxation facilities. Inspired by the urban density of Taipei and the evanescent landscape of the surrounding mountains in the mist, the architecture of the building was designed with a massive, mineral structure that gradually becomes more refined as the façade rises in height. Taiwanese granite, with its raw grain and natural vibrations, was chosen to express this monumentality. The splayed window lintels, cut at an angle towards the large bronze-framed glass panes, design a deep volume with sharp edges creating a sculptural whole. With its unique geometry, the tower stands out like a beacon in the city. The interiors have been designed to contrast with the exterior curved shapes in soft tones and enticing natural materials. The mineral flooring finishes in the reception areas reconnect the interior with the expressive exterior. Some of the joints have been embellished with fine bronze inserts, adding sparkle and delicacy to the light-toned stone. The carpets, which delineate two lounge areas, attract and welcome residents with orthogonal designs that match the layout. The first living room is partitioned in pearlescent ceramic tubes that are set out to form an open-work claustra’s creating an intimate space protected from the streetscape outside. While filtering the light, these elements also reveal an inspiring view of the vegetation climbing the façade. The ceiling is punctuated by two comma-shaped grooves to accommodate the lighting, in an incisive gesture reminiscent of those of Lucio Fontana. Two sculptures designed by RDAI, inspired by a Parisian building lobby decorated by l'Oeuf in the 1960s, have been reinterpreted by local craftsmen. A generously curved sofa, upholstered in a French velvet fabric, blends naturally into the space, inviting residents to relax and unwind. This natural, serene ambience is complemented by chairs with wooden legs and light curly fabric, whose softness is in subtle dialogue with the travertine of the undulating coffee tables. Opposite the imposing bronze-framed entrance door, the reception desk designed by RDAI is sober and delicate, with a light wood crenellation topped by a slightly curved marble top. A second, more private lounge offers warmer, more sustained tones. The tubular screen design, again transposed into claustra screens in front of the exterior glazing, are deployed here in light wood. The carpet, developed locally, echoes the former in its unstructured geometry. A timeless sofa sits alongside iconic natural woven chairs around a masterly coffee table. A dark wood side table adorned with a brass ring adds a subtle note to the ensemble. Opposite, a long marble table designed by RDAI defines the space. On one side, it conceals kitchen units that can be used to host a chef for events, and on the other, timeless chairs in light wood, arranged around the table's single leg, made up of several marble tubes forming a flower in plan. This space is dominated by the unique hand-crafted Io Nimbus suspension lamp. At once organic, light, and kinetic, it emanates a soothing luminance that balances the whole and invites moments of conviviality. The backdrop to this lounge and the entire lobby is a stone wall light from behind, and a slender bookcase designed by RDAI and inspired by Agnès Martin's drawings, with metal shelves spaced out as they rise, a nod to the architecture of the tower. The lifts and corridors have been designed as spaces for strolling around and reflecting, in warm, smoky tones, deliberately subdued by a minimum of indirect light. The apartments have been designed with a sensory aspect in mind, adapting the functions of the space to the natural light. The show apartment, demonstrating the six different typologies of apartments, offers an initial mineral space comprising the entrance hall, kitchen and bathroom in three natural shades, and a second breathing space comprising the living areas and bedrooms, directly facing the bay windows bathed in natural light, treated in warm materials of light wood and powdered stucco in subtle shades. A fine line of bronze, inserted in a hollow joint, marks the base of the walls, signing and linking the whole with a subtle detail. Finally, the rooftop, the crowning glory of the tower, consists of a vast garden planted with trees and coloured with different species of carefully selected plants. It is punctuated by woven wooden pavilions with bold organic shapes that protect small lounges. Various seating and relaxation areas complete the composition. In the centre, a sleek glass box seems to float in the misty strata, housing a gym that offers an immersive physical experience of connecting with nature. Extending from this, a covered terrace shelters a granite block that conceals an outdoor kitchen, an invitation to convivial events.

properties.nom_etablissement: SAM BARON, Bagatelle Bodrum, Yalıkavak, Merkez Mah, Çökertme Cd., 48990 Bodrum/Muğla, Turquie
properties.adresse: Yalıkavak, Merkez Mah, Çökertme Cd., 48990 Bodrum/Muğla, Turquie
properties.description_projet: Opened in July 2022, the Bagatelle Bodrum restaurant and beach club is ideally located on the Yalıkavak Marina, in the famous seaside resort of Bodrum in western Turkey. The perfumes of the Côte d'Azur and the joie de vivre of Bagatelle invite themselves with ease in an atmosphere as refined as it is conconvivial, imagined by the famous designer Sam Baron. Living room, terrace, swimming pool, beach, shop... Everything is there to guarantee memorable moments of delight and sharing with family or friends. At nightfall, facing the sunset plunging over the Aegean Sea, the Bagatelle Bodrum restaurant becomes the unmissable event for vibrant and gourmet evenings. Like the Bagatelle establishments in Saint-Tropez, Miami or Saint-Barth, Sam Baron creates an exceptional setting, where the richness and natural beauty of southern France blend subtly with local culture. Bagatelle Bodrum is thus revealed as a large holiday villa, where each space harmonizes warmly around natural materials such as rattan, associations of striped textiles and declined in shades of blue, white and ocher... This exercise in style is reinforced by the intervention of three European artists, who, for the first time, create unique works around Bagatelle's identity: the Marseille painter Lynda Deleurence, the Lavanderia creative studio - a Portuguese duo composed of Mariana Fernandes and Marta Teixeira - as well as the Istanbul collective Day Studio, founded by Doganberk Demiret Yesim Eröktem.

properties.nom_etablissement: STÉPHANE PARMENTIER, The Webster Palm Springs, 850 N Palm Canyon Dr, Palm Springs, CA 92262, États-Unis
properties.adresse: 850 N Palm Canyon Dr, Palm Springs, CA 92262, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: For the new Webster in Palm Springs, Brazil and more particularly Brasilia and Sao Paulo were the main references for this new Californian address. The dynamic, timeless and geometric architecture of these two cities in the southern hemisphere, marvelously binds to the free and sensual spirit of the Webster. The 'units' that house all the men's and women's collections are reminiscent of the buildings of Brasilia, they are dressed in white sand like the wild beaches of Trancoso, the floor has the color of the Amazonian earth and the lounge area and its furniture are a tribute to Brazilian designers and the genius of Oscar Niemeyer. Here, the XXL works of art, the sculptures and the vintage Brazilian furniture dialogue with, on the ceiling, a sky which ignites the place with its pink reflections like a sunset over Copacabana. The experience is total and always unique, such is the definition of this new journey offered by the Webster in Palm Springs

properties.nom_etablissement: STÉPHANE PARMENTIER, The Webster Toronto , 121 Scollard St, Toronto, ON M5R 1G4, Canada
properties.adresse: 121 Scollard St, Toronto, ON M5R 1G4, Canada
properties.description_projet: The Webster, Canada, Toronto: What was going to be the spirit of the place for this 8th address of the Webster but the first outside the United States? In a natural way, to see almost innate, the desire to look into the codes and the DNA of Webster appeared to us as obvious. The country and also the place and its wonderful central and historical location also strongly inspired us. Laure Hériard Dubreuil opens the doors of this new address to us and tells us about the Webster adventure and its universe. From this discussion, all the DNA codes of the Webster came together to create a vibrant and unique place. Pink: (the timeless signature of Webster). No limit in the love of this marvelous 'vitamin and joyful' color. This color is such a part of the Webster's history that the whole building is now pink, pink with happiness! The stairwell is also all pink a strong and assertive color-block. Even the terrazzo floor of the latter is 'Malabar' pink: a total and strong immersion. A pink hyphen between the floors, as has been this flow since the beginnings of the brand as a strong and sensual identity. As a nod to one of Canada's emblematic animals, a huge all-pink bear by artist Paola Pivi welcomes you as soon as you enter. The Terrazzo: Present from the beginning in the South Beach store in Miami. The terrazzo of the 'retro' Webster floor, listed as a historic monument in Miami, immediately became one of the strong signatures of 'Webster' places. Here in Toronto it is sometimes black, beige, white and of course pink. The Miami spirit: Florida has come to Ontario and in its luggage, a group of palm trees that flourish in the middle of the 'Whisper room'. Also in this space, almost at 360°, a typically 'made in Florida' sunset lines the walls. The exterior signage takes up the pink neon lights of the emblematic dinners of American coolness. Vintage wallpapers: Each Webster project hosts magnificent and now rare retro wallpapers, totally kitsch and quirky. They see each other around the fitting rooms. Sensuality and Femininity: The whole project is clear, luminous but also intimate and warm. The mattified travertine of the benches, corridors and furniture like a SkyLine responds to the Marmorino walls which bring softness and a hushed vibration. The multiple curves of the walls and especially the dome of the 'Whisper room' smooth the reading of the place. Perspectives and curves go hand in hand. Natural light is filtered by curtains of metallic beads which adds softness and intimacy. The parquet, like a Canadian chalet floor, is 'twisted' and is adorned with champagne-colored metal. From rustic, it becomes extremely sophisticated like a jewel with 1000 reflections. The 'Man's Cave': On the top floor, designed as an attic for 'big kids', the men's area welcomes you with a 'Sneakers library', a real library to choose your sneakers without limits. The fully studded central element and the raw travertine niche respond to the special Webster table football.'

properties.nom_etablissement: STÉPHANE PARMENTIER, Giobagnara, P.za San Marco, 289, 30124 Venezia VE, Italie
properties.adresse: P.za San Marco, 289, 30124 Venezia VE, Italie
properties.description_projet: In Venice, Place Saint-Marc, next to the Café Florian, Giobagnara is inaugurating a new place designed by Stéphane Parmentier. In this 'candy box' as Italians fond of beautiful proportions, even if intimate, like to call it, the interior designer wanted to call on a compendium of Giobagnara's know-how: leather in all its forms and straw giving pride of place to travertine, the stone par excellence of Italian architecture. The suede stelae with revisited neo-classical shapes punctuate the space and respond to the centenary columns of the square. The objects on offer are a mix of the most beautiful and emblematic Giobagnara references as well as carefully selected vintage pieces, such as ceramics by Bruno Gambone, sculptures by Mitoraj, and glassware from the 50s and 60s by Venini. A new Italian way of life.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO GGSV, From Paris With Love - Galeries Lafayette Shenzen , Shenzen, Chine
properties.titre_affiche: From Paris With Love - Galeries Lafayette Shenzen
properties.description_projet: An immersive experience between dream and reality: Studio GGSV takes over the windows and store of Galeries Lafayette in Shenzhen . After GL Haussmann, GL Shenzhen in turn invite Studio GGSV to imagine the windows of this department store and offer the public an escape to a dream world. For this occasion, Gaëlle Gabillet and Stéphane Villard have seized on the bucolic and aesthetic codes of the Art Nouveau heritage as well as the symbolism of literati stones. These traditional Chinese stones representing natural elements inspired the duo of artists fascinated by mineral materials. From these inspirations result suspended landscape installations bordering on surrealism like rocks of scholars having left their support to float and create a city in the air. Using digital manipulations, the GGSV studio imagined various digital floral and mineral sculptures in full fulfillment giving the illusion of coming to life before our eyes. They have thus succeeded in transporting us into an augmented dreamlike universe. Elements of the GL heritage such as the dome of the Galeries Haussmann also come to bud on these futuristic decorations. These created from scratch eventually transformed the store into a fantastic immersive garden. Visitors are therefore invited to navigate in this universe on the border between history and virtuality, from Paris to Shenzhen. This installation is a visual experience, where the harmony between past and technology is revealed. A poetic response and a work of audacious composition characteristic of the GGSV studio which pays homage by reinterpreting the GL heritage between Art Nouveau and Digital Art. This artistic encounter playing with cultural borders offers the public a unique immersive experience that unites Paris and Shenzhen. The Shenzhen GLs thus become an artistic theater, where creativity blends with cultural heritage. Design of 8 showcases, 2 videos and 4 corners / opening at the end of July 2023

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO IDAË, The Flying Fish, Chengdu Tianfu International Airport Terminal 2, Domestic Terminal, 2nd Floor, Chengdu, 641400, China
properties.adresse: Chengdu Tianfu International Airport Terminal 2, Domestic Terminal, 2nd Floor, Chengdu, 641400, China
properties.description_projet: This project is inspired by flying fish, evolving in two environments: air and water. They defies the laws of gravity in swimming and flying. In each window designed for Hermès Chendgu boutique, some volumes made out of ropes represent a marine environment, corals in water and clouds in the air. This allow Hermès products to be part of a light movement on and under the sea.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO IDAË, Pipelette, 5 Chome-4-1 Ginza, Chuo City, Tokyo 104-0061, Japon
properties.adresse: 5 Chome-4-1 Ginza, Chuo City, Tokyo 104-0061, Japon
properties.description_projet: “Pipelette” or おしゃべり uses representation of lip synchronisation in order to give a voice to Hermès products. Window display for 15 boutiques Hermès au Japon (Tokyo, Sapporo, Yokohama, Nagoya, Osaka, Umeda et Kobe).
properties.credits_photo: Nacása& Partners Inc./ Courtesy of Hermès Japon

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO IDAË, Pareidolia, Japon, 460-8430 Aichi, Nagoya, Naka Ward, Sakae, 3 Chome−16−1
properties.adresse: Japon, 460-8430 Aichi, Nagoya, Naka Ward, Sakae, 3 Chome−16−1
properties.description_projet: “Pareidolia” is the tendency to perceive a specific, often meaningful image like a face, in a random or ambiguous visual pattern. This project depicts scenes from everyday life filled with pareidolia composed of Hermès objects. Created for Hermès direct store windows, Spring, 2023. Tokyo, Sapporo, Yokohama, Nagoya, Okayama, Hiroshima, Fukuoka.
properties.credits_photo: Nacása& Partners Inc./ Courtesy of Hermès Japon

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO IDAË, Water Calling, Kyoto, Préfecture de Kyoto, Japon
properties.description_projet: Water calling' is a research on groundwater in Kyoto conducted in collaboration with Yoshiko Nagai. How was the groundwater formed? How did the inhabitants develop a water-related culture? In the 1990s, geophysical studies made it possible to quantify the volume of water contained in the water table under the city, equivalent to that of the largest lake in Japan, Biwako. They revealed the relationship between the depth of the bedrock, its composition and the amount of water flowing through it. As early as the Heian era (794-1192), people knew about the abundance of groundwater, but could not explain its origin or course. The book Water calling tells the story of the evolution of the relationship between water and human beings, from the formation of the water table 5 million years ago, to the domestication of water, the emergence of a mythology to the deployment of urban space and its networks, and is composed of twenty felt pen drawings and a text in English/Japanese. Each drawing is associated with an onomatopoeia, translating into Japanese, a sound of water. A double-sided printed cover reveals a story of water in Kyoto through the translucence of the paper. The book was exhibited at the Seikosha bookstore in Kyoto in April 2023.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO JEAN MARC GADY, Pop-up Store Chaumet, Plazza 66, Shanghai
properties.description_projet: Studio Jean-Marc Gady designed the Chaumet pop-up store located in the heart of the prestigious Plaza 66 Building in Shanghai. A luminous and intimate boutique that offers an exclusive experience to visitors of one of the largest shopping malls in the Chinese metropolis. The scenography represents a Chaumet case crowned by a protective field of wheat. The 80m² space offers a unique retail experience by enhancing the codes dear to the Chaumet house in a resolutely contemporary translation. The main room houses an envelope thought as a permeable filter, allowing to link intimacy and openness. Along the walls and in the window, this envelope, made of golden and unbleached blades, evokes strands of wheat in the rhythm of the wind. The curves and movements of the wheat offer a delicate dynamism and a light structure. At the heart of the place, a blue box sits enthroned, a reference to the Chaumet box. This volume contrasts, by its radicalness and its colour, with the lightness and luminosity of the rest of the boutique. In a very fluid sequence, the customer is naturally drawn into a subdued and muffled area, dedicated to the presentation of tiaras and fine jewellery. This exclusive space opens onto a private lounge that immerses the client in the refinement of the Chaumet house.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO JEAN MARC GADY, Watches & Wonders 2023, Genève, Suisse
properties.description_projet: During the Geneva Exhibition Watches & Wonders 2023, Montblanc unveiled its new watches collections. The Jean-Marc Gady studio has designed a 500m² architectural showcase that invites visitors to wander through the glaciers. The visitor enters a mountain cirque where the panorama is drawn in front of him by blocks with a mineral texture made of papier-mâché. These imposing monoliths house the display cases presenting the watches collections. Each showcase features delicate decorations on the themes of the collections: aurora borealis, 14 highest peaks, sea of ice... In the heart of the foyer, Studio Jean-Marc Gady has designed an experience that links time, the art of writing and mountain exploration: the pendulum. This hypnotic installation creates a rendezvous with the visitor by drawing a daily illustration created by the artist Marie de la Ville Baugé. Montblanc writes time.

properties.nom_etablissement: MIAJA DESIGN GROUP, JW Marriott Resort & Spa Maldives, Van'gaaru Island, Atoll 40880, Maldives
properties.description_projet: “JW Marriott Maldives Resort & Spa is a design based on Nature and Fauna with a distinct emphasis on organic elements and modern lines. Comfort and lightness is combined with unique experiences, in a genuine Maldivian getaway atmosphere.“ Isabelle Miaja, Founder, Miaja Design Group.

properties.nom_etablissement: MAXIME D'ANGEAC ARCHITECTURE, Villa P, Genève, Suisse
properties.description_projet: The heart of this highly contemporary architectural project is a magnificent sculptural staircase that winds its way up four floors. This self-supporting technical feat is a light structure made of white lacquered steel, which is set in a magnificent mosaic and glass stairwell. The client wanted a unique house here, like a sculpture, a house that would isolate it from its neighbors and open onto a panorama of Lake Geneva. A basement bathed in light thanks to a double envelope created by the spectacular perimeter wall, reception rooms on the first floor and two floors of living space perched in the trees facing the lake. The heart of the project is a magnificent sculptural staircase that winds its way through four floors. The proportions of this entrance make the best use of planning rules, creating an illusion of space and combining interior and exterior through a curved wood and steel facade that preserves privacy by blending into the beautiful trees of the park. Facing the lake, the glass and steel façade makes the most of the views and sunlight. Cantilevers, technology, and extremely precise details and proportions complete this ultra-contemporary building. (Project is currently being finished. We only have site photos at this time). Translated with ...Learn more (free version)

properties.nom_etablissement: MIAJA DESIGN GROUP, Elevation - Hotel Room Of The Future, London, England
properties.titre_affiche: Elevation - Hotel Room Of The Future
properties.description_projet: MIAJA Design Group showcased their Nature & Asian Philosophy inspired guestroom set at Hospitality Conference Sleep & Eat. The final set presented at the Olympia London showcased a luxurious hotel room with a conservationist ethos, featuring a series of customised Art & Design elements by Isabelle Miaja and carefully selected partners from all over the world. The project brief was to explore one of the major issues today the connection – and disconnection with other human beings as a result of the technology driven world we live in. Sociologists are raising concerned questions about the fact that people spend less time together physically and warning that technology is creating a parallel world distancing us from our humanity. Taking on the theme of “Social FlexAbility” MIAJA Design Group was challenged to design a flexible and engaging space where guests can activate the social experience of their choice.

properties.nom_etablissement: NOCOD STUDIO, Amiri Flagship Store Shanghai, 1225 Nanjing West Road, Jing'an District, Shanghai, China
properties.adresse: 1225 Nanjing West Road, Jing'an District, Shanghai, China
properties.description_projet: The partnership between NOCOD Studio and AMIRI is forged through a first collaboration in 2019. The Californian fashion house is then looking for new talents to support the brand's phenomenal growth. France is, above any other else, the territory where the luxury and the know-how the Californian team seeks is crafted. By choosing a Parisian studio with high creative added-value, AMIRI relies on a French heritage of luxury expertise, while betting on the creative freshness of a certain 'French' touch, whose international influence is no longer to be questioned. The exercise offered by AMIRI is fascinating: find a way to combine the California brand's 'hype casual' vibe with a certain idea of French sophistication. NOCOD's proposal is to engage an exploratory and creative dialogue, in trajection between these two visions. However, the studio's approach remains firmly anchored in the search for an aesthetic narrative, of a certain statutory elegance that past collaborations with great historical houses such as Louis Vuitton or Cartier allowed to question. AMIRI has a singular vision, one of a 'friendly' and unifying luxury it was therefore quite natural that the stores' retail experience should also reflect this uniqueness. By choosing to create real places rather than mere retail spaces, NOCOD imagines open, welcoming shops that embody the warm spirit of Mike Amiri's California. In 2022, NOCOD and AMIRI cosign, in Shanghai, the opening of the brand's first store on Chinese soil, thus inviting the country to discover the codes of 'California style' luxury . In this 600m² flagship, the attention paid to comfort, hospitality, details and materials creates an integral experience, fully-oriented towards the customer. French design is here the support of a common language shared by East and West elegance and audacity make up its vocabulary.

properties.nom_etablissement: NOCOD STUDIO, Amiri Flagship Store Tokyo, Cinnamon, 5 Chome-3-27 Minamiaoyama, Minato City, Tokyo 107-0062, Japon
properties.adresse: Cinnamon, 5 Chome-3-27 Minamiaoyama, Minato City, Tokyo 107-0062, Japon
properties.description_projet: The expansion of the AMIRI s universe beyond the Californian coast reaches out to the Asian continent. The brand's Japanese boutique, which opened in Tokyo mid-2022, admirably embodies the dialogue created between the brand and NOCOD Studio. Located in the trendy district of Minami-Aoyama, the AMIRI Tokyo boutique aims to keep on breaking the codes, precisely those of the kind of too confidential, narrow and exclusive luxury, now outdated. Therefore, the ground floor of the boutique opts for a full-on transparency. Like a 'made in California' space capsule with wide-open doors, the boutique is the spatial embodiment of the brand's California-cool, warm and inviting. Inside the architectural style is elegant and minimalist, and the materials convey a raw sophistication: white concrete walls, brushed chrome, marble. The customer experience is oriented around large rest areas, warmed up by checkerboard carpets and subtle touches of oak wood. The studio's vision also falls into the design of a central furniture piece: a sculptural travertine table, which can also be found in the AMIRI women's boutique at Printemps Haussmann. This project blends the boundaries between disciplines: from the macro-scale of the building to exclusive furniture design, NOCOD puts French context to the test of a definitely cosmopolitan kind of luxury. A luxury where travel, exchanges and creativity are the best possible project levers.

properties.nom_etablissement: NOCOD STUDIO, Amiri Flagship Store Chicago , 46 E Walton St, Chicago, IL 60611, États-Unis
properties.adresse: 46 E Walton St, Chicago, IL 60611, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: As the latest addition to the NOCOD-AMIRI collaboration, after nearly a dozen completed projects, the AMIRI Chicago boutique continues this fertile partnership. The trust and loyalty that each project has been able to consolidate contribute to build a very special, real and deep connection between France and the American brand. Every year for fall and spring, AMIRI exclusively showcases its collections in Paris Fashion Week, and nowhere else. This choice -as well as the partnership binding the Californian fashion house to the French studio throughout the years- expresses more than any other the international appeal of French design's influence. Exporting French creation abroad is for NOCOD the opportunity to keep on questioning the codes of a world that is now changing at unprecedented speed. NOCOD is also dedicated to the exploration for a timeless elegance, that would nonetheless be able to fit in its own time with grace. The undertaken work on the heritage of great French houses (Louis Vuitton, Galeries Lafayette) and on the transmission of their know-how also forges for NOCOD the certainty that the gesture is really at the core of everything. Wouldn't that be what these AMIRI shops are after all? A spatial interpretation of an invitation, of the 'hug', this oh-so American momentum where someone opens its arms towards another, to another.

properties.nom_etablissement: NODESIGN.NET, Designer(s) du Design, Lille / Singapour / Shanghai, Chine / Dubai / Gwangju, Corée du Sud / San José, Costa Rica / Tananarive, Madagascar
properties.description_projet: Imagined by Nodesign, this exhibition presents more than seventy designers, 180 projects, company approaches, personalities, but more importantly the ways designers create, get involved, share and produce in a diversity of practices. From Cyril Diagne to Philippe Starck, via Mathilde Bretillot, the designers presented reflect the universal French spirit. Making an exhibition about design is a challenge. How do you showcase a process, an ambition, a diversity and the singularity of its actors? The exhibition is as much about what is shown as it is about the gaps, the tensions, the differences, the objects and the subjects. We also wanted it to be a demonstration of design: readable, accessible, graspable and didactic. Created for Lille World Design Capital in 2020, the exhibition continues to promote French design around the world by being exported in different formats to Singapore, Shanghai, Dubai, South Korea, Costa Rica and recently to Madagascar. Since 2021, an eponymous book has been published by Editions Fyp.

properties.nom_etablissement: PIERRE GONALONS, Il Salviatino, Via del Salviatino, 21, 50137 Florence Italie
properties.description_projet: Florentine jewel case Il Salviatino nestles in the hills above Florence. Housed in a Renaissance villa, this hotel was designed as an intimate refuge in the heart of a two-hectare park. Redecorated by Pierre Gonalons, it has been restored to its former glory. Pierre Gonalons also designed the hotel's restaurant, which for the occasion becomes a new address for Milan's famous Giacomo house, succeeding Renzo Mongiardino and Studio Peregalli as decorator. This project echoes the second Giacomo he has just signed at Santa Margherita di Ligure, just outside Portofino. This hotel renovation will take place over 3 years, and Pierre Gonalons will completely revamp the hotel for the 2024 season.

properties.nom_etablissement: LUX, La Lune, Kongens Nytorv, Copenhague, Danemark
properties.description_projet: The installation has been commissioned by the City of Copenhagen and STROMMA (danish tourism office) for the Copenhagen Light Festival 2022 and supported by Institut français du Danemark. This new installation on public space, light scenography, was exhibited from 4 to 27 February 2022 on the main square of the city of Copenhagen, in front of the Embassy of France.

properties.nom_etablissement: LUX, Le Monde, Kongens Nytorv, Copenhague, Danemark
properties.description_projet: The installation has been commissioned by the City of Copenhagen and STROMMA (danish tourism office) for the Copenhagen Light Festival 2022 and supported by Institut français du Danemark. This new installation on public space, light scenography, was exhibited from 4 to 27 February 2022 on the main square of the city of Copenhagen, in front of the Embassy of France. Always working on geometric, sober, graphic shapes LUX designed a new original light sculpture in 2022. Seeking its inspiration in the symbols and graphic elements that make up our visual environment: architecture (such as brutalist buildings, spomenik sculptures), decoration and more generally design, LUX created a new light work all in lightness, almost aerial , which sits on a delicate central element. The pieces stand in balance with delicacy. This work entitled « LE MONDE » (the world) as the name of the tarot card (used in the game as well as in divination) symbolizes harmony with Nature, fulfillment, accomplishment, achievement, balance, reciprocation. The artwork is an image to represent the harmony of the Earth: everything is linked and the elements that make up our world are interconnected, influence each other, support each other and are interdependent. The installation will invites visitors to contemplation, imagination and think about the balance in our world : be more attentive to our impact on our environment, act for a more sustainable world.

properties.nom_etablissement: LUX, Le Soleil , Kongens Nytorv, Copenhagen, Denmark
properties.description_projet: The installation has been commissioned by the City of Copenhagen and STROMMA (danish tourism office) for the Copenhagen Light Festival 2022 and supported by Institut français du Danemark. This new installation on public space, light scenography, was exhibited from 4 to 27 February 2022 on the main square of the city of Copenhagen, in front of the Embassy of France. LUX once again turns to the sky for inspiration. The duo of artists likes to pay tribute to celestial objects because they are sources of reverie and hope and have been part of our common culture since the dawn of time. The artwork LE SOLEIL symbolizes the rise and fall and illustrates the cycle of life and of the earth. The light object evokes the sun : a captivating, beneficial, indulgent light, whose warming radiance is rare in winter ... Its energy differs according to the seasons of life, the sun is the source of light, heat and life The Sun is a major focus of space exploration. The sun gives strength it brings abundance and vitality it signifies health and invigoration, clarity and confidence. It is completion, fulfillment. LE SOLEIL warms everything it touches. It is the source of power and energy. It represents the essence of the soul and enlightenment. Its light is omniscient. the sun guides us, it is a constant of human culture and beliefs. We all have the same stars above our heads, we lived on the same planet, we are united, linked, interconnected. Simon & Lucile want to send a message of optimism, and strength. The visitors will have a moment to slow down and contemplate the artwork, an introspective experience and silent observation of the « light of nature ».
properties.credits_photo: 1 : Nicolaï Stagis, 2 : LUX - Lucile Cassassolles, 3 : Yann Couedel

properties.nom_etablissement: MAISON SARAH LAVOINE, Café Joyeux Belgique, Rue Voot 32, 1200 Woluwe-Saint-Lambert, Belgique
properties.description_projet: Maison Sarah Lavoine extends its collaboration with Café Joyeux by reworking the identity of their new cafés / restaurants for future locations from Paris to Lisbon and Brussels. This is a new project that the Architecture Studio has been given a dual mission at the new ephemeral café in the Madeleine: to put the human element at the heart of an ever more pleasant and secure work environment for the 'Joyeux' team members, while creating timeless and warm spaces for the public. The boldness of the functional and warm design, embellished by the iconic bright yellow color, brings an enthusiastic touch to the atmosphere. This decoration punctuated by the play of natural materials such as the wood covering the counters, the parquet floor, a natural and authentic material, as well as the metal and ceramic of the Sicilia tableware, and the 'design' lines, sign the warm and contemporary spaces of these solidarity cafés.

properties.nom_etablissement: MAISON SARAH LAVOINE, Café Joyeux Portugal, Calçada da Estrela 26, 1200-664 Lisboa, Portugal
properties.description_projet: The interior design studio Maison Sarah Lavoine was commissioned to completely rethink the graphic charter of Café Joyeux. The new interiors brighten up the warm and supportive atmosphere of the branded cafés. Café Joyeux is the first coffee shop company to contribute to the professional inclusion of people with mental and cognitive disabilities. Since 2017, the company has employed and trained 90 people in nine locations in France, Belgium and Portugal. The architectural redesign of these spaces with a modern style is revealed through the emblematic colours of the brand, black, white and sunshine yellow. First launched in the branch in La Madeleine, this new brand identity will be rolled out in all the Café Joyeux branches, in France and abroad.

properties.nom_etablissement: MARGAUX KELLER DESIGN STUDIO, L'aparté, Rue de Lausanne 43, 1201 Genève, Suisse
properties.annee_projet: Futur
properties.description_projet: Interior architecture for high standard restaurant in Geneva

properties.nom_etablissement: MARTIAL MARQUET STUDIO, Pawilon Sztuki, Franciszka Kostrzewskiego 1, 00-768 Warszawa, Pologne
properties.description_projet: Located in a park dedicated to the youth of Poznan, this pavilion is realized within the framework of the 10th edition of the international workshop Mood For Wood, invited for the occasion, Martial Marquet accompanied by a group of eleven international students have created and built together a multifunctional space for artistic and creative activities.A structure composed of three elements: a circular bench, a long table and bleachersThe circular bench facilitates the organization of group activities, for example, discussions about art, conferences, meetings with guest artists. The second element, a long table lined with benches, allows for co-creation during painting, drawing and modeling classes. On the other hand, the stepped structure creates an auditorium and at its highest point offers an unobstructed view of the park. The entire construction is based on a modular principle developed to allow rapid construction, but also ease of reuse if the construction proves obsolete in the future.
properties.credits_photo: Martial Marquet Studio - Mood For Wood

properties.nom_etablissement: MATALI CRASSET, Dododo Bookstore, Power Station of Art, Chine, Shanghai, District de Huangpu
properties.adresse: Power Station of Art, Chine, Shanghai, District de Huangpu
properties.description_projet: In collaboration with Consortium Museum, DIjon: Franck Gautherot & Seundguk Kim dododo bookstore is the bookshop of the Power Station of art, a museum of contemporary art housed in a former power station in Shanghai's Bund district. The bookstore includes a space for creative workshops, a conference area and a café. This bookshop space for Power Station of Art is based on the principles of the Presses du Réel bookshop at the Consortium Museum in Dijon, with an enlarged version. The project is based on an homage to François Truffaut's film Fahrenheit 451, based on Ray Bradbury's science-fiction novel of the same name, incorporating a reference to the monorail featured in the film. The monorail is thus the heart of the set-up: it avoids cluttering the space with mobile suspended storage-wagons, which can be rolled to different locations, and are accessible from both sides. The center with the monorail becomes a point of attraction, with new products on the outside and a selection of gifts on the inside. At the heart of the layout is an active space: on the one hand, a studio for materializing the online shop and doing photo shoots to create images for PSA's digital platform and social media, thanks to a specially-designed cyclo-regie on the other, a space where small groups can sit around a table and, at other times, present books for discussion or signing.... The bookshop is deployed here in a larger area around the circle, which is made up of 7 coloured segments that extend into 7 radiating branches from the monorail, corresponding to the 7 sectors of activity of the bookshop. Each color of the central structure of the suspended library refers to a larger space made up of shelves, tables and other devices dedicated according to the offer presented. The colors form a gradation that develops in the space, revolving around the central circle. The do book section is orange, the section presenting the museum's publications and editions orange-red, and so on. This space is materialized by a colored strip on the floor, which is the main path to access the section's offerings, starting from the center or the other end. All additional structures are formal variations of the central monorail's load-bearing structures. They are available in widths of 3 meters, 2 meters and 1.20 meters to adapt to the available space. They are interchangeable, as only a label on the lecterns on either side carries the color. A wheeled pedestal can be fitted underneath to hold stock to complement the taller pedestals, which are arranged around the perimeter along the walls. The structure is also available as a display case, positioned near the two entrances. Four structures can be moved outside for events.

properties.nom_etablissement: MATALI CRASSET, Sid et le Monde de dessous, West Bund Museum, Xuhui District, Shanghai, Chine, 200232
properties.titre_affiche: Sid et le Monde de dessous
properties.adresse: West Bund Museum, Xuhui District, Shanghai, Chine, 200232
properties.description_projet: The Creative Gallery - Playground is a space designed for young audiences in this Chinese branch of the center Pompidou x West Bund museum project in Shanghai. matali crasset has created a world where children can explore the world below Sid and the world below. This project is based on the idea of giving the lead role to female characters: like us humans, they are in charge of the evolution of their species, and must adapt to the imaginary world in which they live. The main character is Sid, a small oak acorn. 'At the outset, there was a desire to discover a new territory, at seed level, one meter underground, with its own matalicrasset ecosystem, its own plant species, its animal kingdom, its smells and sounds... It's a world to share with its characters, little seeds that guide the visitor. It's an original work that encourages exploratory practices and questions about a little-known underground world. Experimentation encourages understanding of existing interactions with the surrounding world, and reflection on the ecological challenges facing our society. The installation calls for creative and respectful behavior. Everyone takes part in its construction, and at the same time, collective adventures are planned. It's also a world of fun and wonder. You love exploring imaginary worlds, so welcome to the world of Sid, a little oak acorn, and the world below.' -

properties.nom_etablissement: MAXIME D'ANGEAC ARCHITECTURE, Silenseas Orient Express Boat, Caraïbes
properties.annee_projet: Futur
properties.description_projet: 140 years after the launch of its first luxury trains, the Orient Express legend continues with the launch of the world's largest sailing ship, Orient Express Silenseas. A revolution in maritime history, and a fabulous project that pushes the limits of what is possible. Inspired by the golden age of the French Riviera, Orient Express Silenseas will recall the era when writers, artists, painters, sovereigns and movie stars discovered between Monte-Carlo, Saint-Tropez, the Cap d'Antibes, Cannes and its Croisette, a refinement tinged with insouciance and joie de vivre, calling for an escape. A 220-meter long treasure of the seas (with a tonnage of 22,300 UMS), she will celebrate the Art of Travel according to Orient Express through her 54 Suites with an average surface area of 70 square meters, including her monumental Presidential Suite of 1,415 square meters (including 530 square meters of private terrace). Its 2 swimming pools including a swim lane, its two restaurants and its speakeasy bar will add to the quintessence of luxury, absolute comfort and dream. A tribute to artists and culture, Orient Express Silenseas will invite you to the world of entertainment in its Amphitheatre-Cabaret and private recording studio. A unique travel experience punctuated by the winds, where spa treatments, meditation sessions and stopovers to discover cultural treasures will help you disconnect from time. (The project will be delivered in 2026, it is in its design stage, for the moment we can only show the visuals from the outside).

properties.nom_etablissement: EMMANUELLE SIRVEN, Northcote Road Period House, Northcote Rd, Londres, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: This project concerns the refurbishment of a Victorian house, in the lovely and lively neighbourhood of Northcote road in Battersea, London. The renovation included the whole ground floor with its hallway, staircase, double living room guest loo and kitchen that leads to a lovely rear garden. On the 1st floor the 3 bedrooms were renovated for the parents and their 2 children of 3 and a few month old. The project needed to have a work space that should be discreet for the family moments. This young and dynamic family were looking for colours and modernity in the design, choices of finishes and pieces of furniture. It unfolded on 2 years and was completed last year.

properties.nom_etablissement: EMMANUELLE SIRVEN, Brook Green Bathrooms, Brook Grn, Londres, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: This project concerns the renovation of both bathrooms of the property located in a high street house by Brook green in London. Both bathrooms were entirely striped down and we created two very different atmospheres: sophisticated and modern for the parents and colourful and fresh for the children

properties.nom_etablissement: EN BANDE ORGANISEE, Offecct Stockholm Furniture Fair, Stockholmsmässan, Mässvägen 1, 125 30 Älvsjö, Sweden
properties.description_projet: For the Stockholm Furniture Fair, we designed an inspiring space to showcase the world and products of Scandinavian furniture brand Offecct (FLOKK Group). We imagined the booth as a microarchitecture that presents the world of Offecct. It is a microarchitecture with very large openings that invite to enter and discover different workspaces. The color is very important in this space because first it gives a very strong and bold identity to the booth. But also, Color is a great tool to create and structure space. As an interior designers, I appreciate furniture and its proportions in a space, in resonance with the other objects and volumes that surround it. Color allows to see the space (and the furniture) as a « wholeness' like a landscape. I want people discover the product but also the workspace it create. Color impacts the appearance of the objects. It allows a focus on the curves, textures, ...

properties.nom_etablissement: FRANKLIN AZZI ARCHITECTURE, Ep Yaying - Shanghai, Hengshanfang, 880 Hengshan Rd, Xujiahui, Xuhui District, Shanghai, Chine, 200030
properties.adresse: 880 Hengshan Rd, Xujiahui, Xuhui District, Shanghai, Chine, 200030
properties.description_projet: The Chinese brand EP YAYING called on Franklin Azzi to design the new architectural concept of Shanghai, Jiaxing, Pékin and New York's flagships, and an architectural bible to deploy the brand in 300 international stores. Faithful to his passion for creative encounters and collaborations, Franklin Azzi has united his vision with that of fashion designer Serge Ruffieux to establish a new architectural concept and architectural bible for Chinese high-end brand EP YAYING. Reflecting the approach of the iconic label in the revival of luxury goods and Chinese heritage – the name EP YAYING means ‘pledge of quality’ – Franklin Azzi drew from Oriental cultural references and know-hows to design a minimal/maximal concept. Combining Chinese culture with the French art of living and hospitality, the architect's contemporary aesthetic is hybrid, bold and unprecedented. This approach resulted in a program of spaces dedicated to experimentation and strolling, cultivating oxymoron in every detail, and evolving uniquely with each new store. The architecture of the boutiques - in both new and existing buildings - focuses on transparency, openness to the outdoors and integration of nature. The space dedicated to the brand joins the public space in a principle of fluid urbanity. The raw beauty of the materials, such as jade and concrete, is combined with the elegance of lacquer work and embroidery. The boutiques reveal their singularity in a play of contrasts between stark simplicity and maximalism, the association of rough and smooth surfaces, matte and gloss colors, and the mixing of traditional Chinese craftsmanship and the occidental vision of the two creators. From floor to ceiling, through the furniture and changing rooms designed as transition and exhibition spaces in dialogue with the overall scheme, an unusual journey was designed, composed of aesthetic and sensorial resonances. A means for the architect to bring modernity and craftsmanship into dialogue in an original approach that sees each new EP YAYING boutique as a unique venue.
properties.credits_photo: 1 et 3 : Matjaz Tancic, 2 : Franklin Azzi Architecture
