properties.nom_etablissement: FRANKLIN AZZI ARCHITECTURE, Ep Yaying - Jiaxing , Chang Sheng Zhong Lu, District de Xiuzhou, Jiaxing, Zhejiang, Chine

properties.nom_etablissement: ID-WAD, Les Myriades de Bouskoura (marjane), Marjane Les Myriades Bouskoura, Bouskoura, Maroc
properties.adresse: Marjane Les Myriades Bouskoura, Bouskoura, Maroc
properties.description_projet: Concept design, signage, wayfinding and author surveillance Opening 2022 / 19 000 GLA Inspired by nature and punctuated by the rhythms of the customer journey, ID-wad sets the pace by orchestrating a symphony that adapts to the expectations of all users. In this project, contemplation, recreation and experiences are subtly mixed around colorful signage in order to that the Bouskourians do not lose a beat.

properties.nom_etablissement: JEAN-CHARLES DE CASTELBAJAC, The People of Tomorrow, West Bund Museum, Xuhui District, Shanghai, Chine, 200232
properties.adresse: West Bund Museum, Xuhui District, Shanghai, Chine, 200232
properties.description_projet: The People of Tomorrow,' a new interactive installations exhibition presented by the Centre Pompidou × West Bund Museum Project, will meet its Chinese audiences from March 8 to August 31, 2023. For his Chinese debut, the fashion icon and esteemed French artist Jean-Charles de Castelbajac creates a world of symbols, the most powerful signs of our times, leading the visitors on a journey of discovery and creation and experience his colorful and poetic artistic world. Today's creativity is tomorrow's motivation, 'The People of Tomorrow ' is a gift from the artist to awaken and stimulate everyone's innate artistic sensibility. The young people of today are the future of the world tomorrow, this exhibition is going to resonate with all those who are still young at heart!

properties.nom_etablissement: KNGB, Showroom Casamance Misia, Design Centre, Chelsea Harbour, Lots Rd, London SW10 0XE, Royaume-Uni
properties.adresse: Design Centre, Chelsea Harbour, Lots Rd, London SW10 0XE, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: Project in progress, visuals to come. KNGB are involved in creating the 1st flagship store for the two Misia Casamance brands on the 3rd floor of the London Design Centre. Casamance called on KNGB to design the showroom and bespoke furniture to present the products of the two brands. The collection will be designed and manufactured in France. Collaboration ADD France

properties.nom_etablissement: LAURA GONZALEZ, Cartier New York 5th Avenue, 653 5th Ave, New York, NY 10022, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: Iconic boutique on New York's 5th Avenue, showcasing the creativity and expertise of more than 50 French artisans. Each floor has been redesigned to promote a sense of warmth and hospitality, further enhancing the distinctive experience of visiting a Cartier boutique. The commissioned artworks draw parallels with the Maison's exquisite craftsmanship, while highlighting its rich history. Laura Gonzalez called on French and New York artisans, including Atelier Midavaine and Etienne Rayssac, to decorate the space, while exploring new collaborations with mosaicists Béatrice Serre and Mathilde Jongquiere, as well as Brooklyn-based sculptor Peter Lane.

properties.nom_etablissement: LAURA GONZALEZ, New York Splendor, 24 E 64th St Unit 1R, New York, NY 10065, États-Unis
properties.adresse: 24 E 64th St Unit 1R, New York, NY 10065, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: Perfectly named, New York Splendor, this exhibition will occupy the first floor of Invisible Collection's The Townhouse with an exceptional selection of furniture by Laura Gonzalez, including pieces created in collaboration with specialist designers from 19M, Chanel's Métiers d'Art. Inspired by the elegance of The Townhouse's architecture, Laura will present a modern, authentic interpretation of grand New York entertaining, with chinoiserie from the house of Pierre Frey, combined with the travel inspirations, contemporary materials and vibrant prints that forge her style.

properties.nom_etablissement: LE CANN, Inhouse, Tel-Aviv, Israël
properties.description_projet: Commissioned by our client, a real estate developer working between France and Israel, we wanted to take advantage of and embrace the strong constraints of the site for the development of its offices in Tel Aviv. Located on the ground floor of a concrete building, the space was inevitably very cluttered with carriers and various ducts and had only one facade with natural light. The space has been designed as a gallery along this typical Bauhaus-style glass roof of the city. The recreated main circulation, along the latter, serves three curved mineral alcoves, each hosting a function: meeting room, workspace and kitchen. The place is deliberately open in order to favor light and a feeling of volume. The more confidential rooms, such as the toilets and a 'phone booth' entirely upholstered in velvet, are pushed back behind the alcoves against the blind wall. The softness and the enveloping nature of the mineral, like the Negev desert, is highlighted by the contrasts of reflections. Terracotta, travertine and mineral plaster are set against a variation of lacquer, brushed metal, polished metal and mirror creating stunning vibrations and depths. The space becomes the showcase of the company's know-how reflecting the le cann style.

properties.nom_etablissement: BISMUT&BISMUT, Nomadhome x Bismut, Dubaï, Émirats arabes unis
properties.description_projet: The project is a 1000sqm vast house designed by the agency in the Jumeirah 1 neighborhood, dedicated to interior design and home decor. It was thought and designed as a private residence: living rooms, dining room, bedrooms, large kitchen, spa, bathrooms, terraces. Daniel and Michel Bismut’s universe reveals in a 200sqm space, showcasing a large selection of furniture, light fixtures, as well as limited edition pieces from their collection. The decor picks up Bismut & Bismut’s signature codes. NomadHome X Bismut is designed like an immersive experience inviting visitors to acquire a piece of furniture or decor, to discover artisanal expertise.

properties.nom_etablissement: BISMUT&BISMUT, The Wave, Comporta, Portugal
properties.description_projet: For this new project in Portugal, Daniel and Michel Bismut have designed two luxurious villas with ocean views. On these bare plots emerge two contemporary residences but blend perfectly into the local landscape of Comporta, by their natural and warm materials and their soft colors. Each house is differentiated by its style: one is more traditional with the look of a cabin, whilst the other is drawn in curves like a wave. By designing the exteriors and interiors of these villas, Daniel and Michel have signed a new project promoting French architecture abroad.

properties.nom_etablissement: BORELLA ART DESIGN, Amelia Hotel , Amelia Hotel, 9620 Albena, Bulgarie
properties.description_projet: Amelia Hotel 5* 100 keys is located along the black sea in Bulgaria. It is the first thematic hotel in Albena, dedicated to the first woman pilot who crossed the Atlantic - Amelia Earhart. Inspired by her story, Borella Art Design studio, Paris, recreate part of her biography through numerous details running in the interiors of the hotel. The aim is to give the guest, the feeling of living the experience of the pilots of those times: flying in the sky over the vast ocean, living in an airplane cabin, or having dinner in the cafe of the pilots. the studio has studied the entire renovation of the hotel , lobbies, restaurant, bar, bed and bath rooms. The rooms of the Hotel Amelia offer a unique experience, like a journey suspended in the air, within an airplane cabin, with the rivet wallpaper, mirrors like windows plane, the headboard is reminiscent of the soft leather of the comfortable seats of airplanes, the metal-hulled seat simulates the aviator’s seat or the carpet evoking the map of the winds. The restaurant is inspired from a mess of the officers dedicated to the pilots. The scenography is inspiring from the style of the period (1930th.), Christine and Nicola Borella, reinterpret the theme, presenting graphism, illustrations, materials, colours, shape of the furniture, printed on metal meshes. The restaurant offers a suspended moment in time with the 'mess hall' atmosphere of a 1928 airport. This place is a scenography in which the customer becomes in a way like an actor, and lets himself be inspired and immersed in a complete universe of an aviator. The materials leather, wood, chrome, golden brasses allow an essential link with the time of the heroic pilots of the Aeropostale… The room, the corridors and the public areas are aiming to surprise the visitor for him to discover more and more details, and be willing to renew his visit and staying. After Charles Lindbergh's first flight from New York to Paris in 1927, the idea arose in the minds of the publishers of the story of his crossing, that a similar impact could accompany the first crossing of the Atlantic by plane, by a woman. After several attempts of pilots’ women, Hilton Railey asks the courageous Amelia Erhard to cross the Atlantic by plane, assisted by co-pilot and mechanic Louis Gordon. Leaving Trepassey, they landed near Burry Port, Wales, after 20 h 40 min flight. Amelia Earhart's trip from Trepassey is on display at the National Air and Space Museum. Amelia becomes a glorious aviator, and decide in 1932 to cross the Atlantic solo, like Lindberg did: the first transatlantic flight by a woman. Fulfilling the promise, she had made in 1928. Earhart took off on the morning of 20 May 1932 from Harbour Grace (province of Newfoundland and Labrador) in a Lockheed Vega and after a solo flight of 14 h 56 min landed in a meadow at Culmore, north of Londonderry in Northern Ireland becoming then the first woman to cross the Atlantic Ocean alone by plane.

properties.nom_etablissement: CABINET BEAUCLAIR, Exhibition Amber: Baltic Gold, 83 Tat Chee Ave, Kowloon Tong, Hong Kong
properties.adresse: 83 Tat Chee Ave, Kowloon Tong, Hong Kong
properties.description_projet: The exhibition “Amber: Baltic Gold”, originally slated for spring 2020, has been four years in the planning. Many things have happened since then, and it has been worth the wait for it is truly a great pleasure to be able once again to welcome international loans at the Indra and Harry Banga Gallery. The support of the patrons of City University of Hong Kong and of the Indra and Banga Gallery was indispendable in making this exhibition come to fruition. The idea for this ambitious exhibition came from Dita Podskocija, Via-Ars founder, and Gilles Bonnevialle, the French cultural councillor to Latvia (2015-2019), who was previously Consul for Culture, at the French Consulate General in Hong Kong and Macau, and head of “Le French May” festival (2009-2013). They worked in close collaboration with three colleagues at museums in Latvia and Lithuania: Inese Baranovska at the Latvian National Museum of Art Anita Meinarte at the National History Museum of Latvia and Sigita Baguzaite-Talackiene at the Palanga Museum, Lithuania. And the idea took shape of an exhibition showing the influence of amber from its Baltic origins to Europe and Asia. The extremely generous loans by Betty Lo and Kenneth Chu from the Mengdiexuan Collection in Hong Kong represent almost a third of the total exhibits their contribution now offers a rare overview of the role and use of amber in China from the Han through the Qing dynasties. The loans from the National History Museum of Latvia and the Latvian National Museum of Art together provide an overview of three thousand years of amber artworks from the Neolithic to the contemporary period. And these are supplemented by the wonderful examples from the Georgs Romulis collection, a famous jeweller whose personal collection includes not only pieces of his own work but also rare examples of amber inclusions, extremely old pieces, and ones with various colours and shapes. Numerous non-Baltic European examples were provided by private collector Philippe Thomas, while two splendid Baroque artworks were generously loaned to us by the Association Trésors de Ferveur and the Fondation Fourvière–Musée d’art religieux. The Liang Yi Museum also entrusted to us four of their precious objects, incrusted with amber, and we had the pleasure of being able to exhibit contemporary pieces by the French designers and artists: Kam Tin and Aline Putot-Toupry and Bruno Toupry. We would also like to thank Michel Perreault and Clément Zanolli for providing the impressive synchrotron images, as well as the ESRF Heritage Database for Palaeontology, Evolutionary Biology and Archaeology for allowing their reproduction in the exhibition. The visual experience of the exhibition was created by Frederic Beauclair and the audio-visual and cinematic installations of Nicolas Patrzynski, who together transformed this into a magical event. And together, Gilles Bonnevialle and Dita Podskocija made sure all the parts came together.

properties.nom_etablissement: CHZON, Cowley Manor, Cowley Manor Experimental, Cowley, Cheltenham GL53 9NL, Royaume-Uni
properties.adresse: Cowley Manor Experimental, Cowley, Cheltenham GL53 9NL, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: Built in 1695, this manor has changed hands a number of times until James Horlick became the owner in 1895 doing most of the alterations of the building, together with Colonel Heber Percy, the next owner.  This manor, now turned into an hotel also has stables, a new modern extension, and a large spa, counting 36 rooms in total and numerous living rooms : garden room, game room, a cocktail bar, a cocktail lounge, a restaurant, a library, a mud room,  two swimming pools …  Overall we wanted to do what we love to do : a mix of geometric elements, a mix of styles, of eras, celebrating the multiple alterations of the buildings from 1695 to the 2000s. So at the end a joyeux bordel.  Our main inspiration was of course the building itself mixing very classical inspirations as a tribute to the original manor : baledaquin beds, blurred maple, verdigris, sophisticated rattan furniture … mixed with contemporary elements such as : enameled lava, lime walls, very graphic fabrics and carpets, full upholstered furniture, bold colors, glossy lacquer and a lot of …. checkerboard patterns !  And this was a tribute to Alice in Wonderland : Lewis carol has written his Alice at Cowley Manor inspired by the grounds of Cowley Manor !  As a wink, we have hidden small doors, small elements from Alice on the carpets and checks everywhere : on rugs, carpets, fabrics, painted on walls, at different scales, different colors, tone on tone, sculpted, in lava …

properties.nom_etablissement: CONSTANCE GUISSET STUDIO, Exhibition Surprise party, Institut français Milano, Corso Magenta, 63, 20123 Milano
properties.adresse: Institut français Milano, Corso Magenta, 63, 20123 Milano
properties.description_projet: The French Institute Milano invites the designer to unveil her work from April 18 to May 13, 2023. The exhibition has been conceived as a colorful bubble, a parenthesis in the frenzy of Milan and its Design Week. On the occasion of this carte blanche, the visitor will be invited to discover Constance Guisset's creations in a festive and evanescent scenography, evoking the world of entertainment. Through a work of colored lights, the objects in shades of white will be revealed as they have never been seen, revealing their silhouettes and their materials. The installation will be an invitation to embark on a spectacular journey, to venture into a colored haze, to take time for contemplation. Visitors will be encouraged to touch the objects, even to try them out, to extend their exploration. The entire exhibition will present the designer's balancing act, between research and realization. As a counterpoint to the completed projects, the creative process will be evoked through drawings, sketches or even inspirational films, revealing the sensitive world preceding the conception of the objects. The exhibition will also be an opportunity to highlight the studio's work as a whole, through installation, interior architecture and scenography projects. Thus, visitors will wander among the furniture in the central space, before reaching an alcove plunged into darkness where the architectural, scenographic and stage design projects will be revealed.

properties.nom_etablissement: CURIOSITY, Graff Monaco, Monaco
properties.description_projet: A new Graff boutique designed by Curiosity just opened in Casino De Monte-Carlo, following the brands’ Tokyo and Osaka flagship stores. A key destination for high jewellery, Monaco has been an important location for the luxury jeweller ever since it opened its first Graff store outside of the United Kingdom. An opportunity to opt for a resolutely modern interior and style yet respecting the Principality regulations of balancing well the design with the exterior historical façade of the venerable palace-like Casino, that is arguably the most famous building in the city. The new boutique, designed by Gwenaël Nicolas, occupies a space that is as luxurious and welcoming with its bright interior. Appropriate to a key destination of high jewellery, the store is the completely refined Graff diamonds world in the beautiful balance of classic exterior and modern interior, which offers a comfortable harmony, yet notably contrasting, when customers enter the store. The bright white space welcomes the visitors in elegant atmosphere after entering through the grandeur, historical facade. As the unique feature for Monaco store, a glass chandelier with delicate orchid-like, opal petals and transparent glass framework, designed by Curiosity and produced in collaboration with Lasvit, infuse sophistication and modernity into the space, which complete the whole impression of this store.

properties.nom_etablissement: CURIOSITY, M-i-d Kobe, Kobe, Préfecture de Hyōgo, Japon
properties.description_projet: Curiosity designed a blue labyrinth, a new concept store for the m-i-d brand, which opened in the Daimaru Kobe Store. Situated on the 3rd floor of the popular department store in Kobe, the fashionable city in the Kansai region, the store invites shoppers from multiple dimensions opened widely to corridors. The store showcases only the selected collections of m-i-d’s 5 segmented brands, with the individual characters of these brands appearing. The remarkable and selected items are equally balanced, and their individual characters appear between vertical slab walls of different heights, offering fun to browse the items in the random layout in a soft tone. The design, conceived as a labyrinth, is deconstructed to create new perspectives and unexpected configurations. The vertical walls, reflected by mirrors, surround the customer in an installation-like retail environment. The walls and floors are unified with the same material and a soft shade of blue, carefully chosen for this store to express its urban character. The dynamic onyx pattern of large slab walls leads the impression of the interior. In keeping with the sophisticated atmosphere, the furnishings include large stone tables in the same pattern as the tiled walls and a sofa in the same shade of blue. The rust-bronze metal stages provide an effective accent, creating balanced sequences with the texture of the walls and the line of the ceiling.

properties.nom_etablissement: DIDIER FIUZA FAUSTINO / MESARCHITECTURE, Paula Rego. There And Back Again, Goseriede 11, 30159 Hannover, Allemagne
properties.titre_affiche: Paula Rego. There And Back Again
properties.description_projet: The aim of the scenography is to emphasize on the contemporaneity of Paula Rego’s work (1935 - 2022) as well as to echo the violence of the world she describes. Walls to hang her paintings have been designed with protruding parts, giving them a grotesque appearance resembling the grotesque figures of the artist. Their wrapping with heat-shrink white film, with it stretched and wrinkled parts, give a sense of both tension and sensuality.

properties.nom_etablissement: DIDIER FIUZA FAUSTINO / MESARCHITECTURE, Exist/resist. Didier Fiúza Faustino Works, 1995 - 2022, Av. Brasília, 1300-598 Lisboa, Portugal
properties.description_projet: EXIST/RESIST is Didier Fiúza Faustino's first institutional retrospective exhibition, spread over two spaces: the oval gallery (760 m2) and the project room (436 m2). The oval gallery has been designed as an analogue data centre. It is occupied by a central space, bordered on either side by six walls, spaced apart from each other, forming a central nave. While each wall acts as an exhibition panel, some of the walls have circular cut-outs that reveal other works in a more intimate way. The cut-out circles, painted blue, are like pedestals on which the sculptures rest. The ensemble is topped by 24 2.50 m long lights that create a ceiling of light.

properties.nom_etablissement: EL'LE ARCHITECTS, Les Roses, 5 Rue Flammang, 5618 Mondorf-les-Bains, Luxembourg
properties.description_projet: The gastronomic restaurant 'Les Roses' has been refurbished to be more elegant and modern. The splendid custom-made carpet recalls Monet's water lilies and the Giverny garden. The interior architecture came to support the sober and modern kitchen of the new Chef, and the colors and materials were chosen with regard to the aesthetics of the dishes.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER ARCHITECTURE 64, The River House, Project 32 Road, Accord NY
properties.description_projet: The River House, located on a steep wooded site in upstate New York, benefits from an amazing view of the surrounding landscape and river on the property. The house consists of two interlocked volumes of differentiated programming and material The larger zinc and glass volume houses the living spaces while the intersection wood volume, more enclosed and intimate, contains the more private bedrooms and bathrooms. The house is structured with local wood using a series of glue laminated columns and beams, creating a protective expansive cantilever above the deck, which itself cantilevers out of the sloped hilltop, along with the bedroom volume, to hide the access road from the interior and provide a sense of cascading to mimcic the river waterfall downslope. The choice of natural and local materials blend the house to its environment. The plan provides an interior transition from the more enclosed entrance side of solid facades with small windows, to open facade with expansive views to the landscape and river. The entrance and kitchen, two steps above the living room, allows the owners to fully enjoy the view and sound of the river from everywhere within the living spaces. By creating a double height space with a sloping roof, the feeling of openness towards the forested slope to the water is emphasized and reinforced through the large stone fireplace, which is also visible from outside decks and driveway approach, tying in the facades, gazing and roof forms.The plan of the bedrooms and bathrooms is more intimate, where each room has a large window framing specific views of the property and creating connections between inside and outside while retaining privacy from other rooms as well as the surrounding decks. A custom tiling pattern was designed to bring a nature feeling of the landscape patterns to the adjacent bathrooms.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER DONATIEN CARRATIER, Hyatt Regency Phuket, Phuket, Mueang Phuket, Province de Phuket 83000, Thaïlande
properties.adresse: 16, 12 Moo 6 Kamala, Amphur Kathu, Phuket 83150, Thaïlande
properties.description_projet: Total Hotel Renovation, All Rooms, Nahm SPA, All Day Restaurant, Pool Bar, Teppanyaki Restaurant, Wedding Event Center, lobby.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER PAF, Inflatable  2, Brussels
properties.description_projet: For the sixth edition of Collectible Fair in Brussels, the studio was asked to design an ephemeral installation to occupy the entrance/exit area of the fair. In response to the carte blanche given to it by the fair's founders, the studio designed a scenography and signage based on inflatables, the result of research into the material, its aesthetics and its longevity. The installation, which can be viewed from all angles, is hung high up and serves as a spatial reference point for visitors inside the gigantic Tour & Taxis complex hosting the fair, without interfering with the legibility of the works on display. Like the inflatable architectures created in the 1970s, the scenography designed for Collectible Fair is easy to transport and store, designed to be re-used in other applications. Its weight/volume ratio makes it particularly ideal for ephemeral installation. The result of several months of experimentation, the inflatables are made in collaboration with a craftsmen's workshop. Particular attention is paid to the quality of the materials sourced, and to ensuring that they are recycled. Following on from his work on Collectible, Christopher Dessus, founder of Paf atelier, was invited by the Université de design de Montréal to hold a workshop lasting several days with 19 students from the space design section. Following the inflatable elements produced for the Collectible project, the workshop's aim was to reuse them in order to work with the students to explore the infinite possibilities of arrangement, using only rope and inflatable cylinders. The aim of this research with the students was also to produce an exhibition. Entitled 'The languages of the possible', the exhibition is the culmination of numerous discussions and a rigorous process on the theme of public space, using rope and twenty-eight inflatables as constraints. The exhibition is part of a multi-disciplinary approach combining sketching, scenographic design, installation and signage. As a result of these various projects, and the ever-growing number of questions raised about inflatables, the studio has come up with the idea of working with Pli to publish a book on the subject in 2024.

properties.nom_etablissement: AURELIEN CHEN, Dragon Mountain Tourist Center, Zhulongshan, Rizhao, Shandong, China
properties.description_projet: Between Earth and Sky, a fragmented architectural complex. An architectural complex adapting to its natural surroundings The entrance to Dragon Mountain natural tourist site is marked by a view of the mountain within the axis of the site’s entrance alley. This alley splits into two separate lanes once entered site: one lane climbs up towards the mountain and the other descends slightly towards two small ponds, situated on a lower level and surrounded by trees. Aiming to adapt the complex to this natural site, the main architectural stance was to fragment the 3000 m² surface into five architectural elements adapting to the topography and the natural context of the site. The five architectural elements are situated and organized around a small square. The design of these buildings is pure and slender. They are low on the side facing the site entrance and they rise up and grow in height towards their mountain side. On their lower side, with their mass, these buildings are connected to the Earth. On their higher side, with their geometry, they reach for the Sky, reminding us that, according to Chinese tradition, the human being is closely connected to the Sky and the Earth, and according to Taoism it is part of a Cosmic Triad with Heaven and Earth. There is a dialogue between the curved buildings and a tension between volumes and empty spaces. In these empty spaces, landscape perspectives are created in order to frame the mountain. Entrance Gate In China, entrances to modern touristic sites usually follow a standard approaching sequence: a public square with a monumental sculpture at its centre followed by an entrance gate reminiscent of the traditional ones, a ticket counter and, lastly, an information and welcome centre. Here, the entrance gate to the site is incorporated into the architectural composition. It houses the ticket counter on one side and the security staff area on the other. Its mass is both architecture and sculpture. It is a visual landmark and attracts the visitors in the distance. The gate is composed by three rows of arched walls that, in a way common to urban public spaces, creates and delimits the public square just outside the site. Walls are rooted in the ground and they reach for the sky in their centre, reminding of the mountain peaks and also the verticality of the Cosmic Triad Earth- Human Being – Heaven. There is no portal. Instead, a void, a void becoming a landscape frame on the mountain peaks far in the distance. The consecutive walls remind of the fortifications that once surrounded cities and traditional palaces and create a peculiar sequence of approach: in their intervals, the visitor discovers the entrances to each separate building. Materials Stone cladding expresses the concept of mass connected to the Earth and allows a delicate integration of the gate with its natural surroundings and with local architecture. Raw concrete made from wood formwork reminds of the irregularity of natural elements and can be easily built even by unskilled workers. A natural screen made of natural bamboo sticks creates a subtle layer between massive concrete/stone and transparent glass. Credits Architects: Aurelien Chen / Urban and rural planning and design institute of CSCEC Partners in charge: Aurelien Chen, Wu Yixia (Urban and rural planning and design institute of CSCEC) Lead Architect: Aurelien Chen Design Institute: Urban and rural planning and design institute of CSCEC Design team: Aurelien Chen, Ma Jing, Wang Manyu Location: Rizhao, China Area: 1500 m² Client: Rizhao Fada Jituan Completion date: 2023 Photographs : © Aurelien Chen

properties.nom_etablissement: AURELIEN CHEN, Leaf Pavilion, Yongyingqu South Road, Beijing, China
properties.description_projet: Two tree leaves on top of each other, their shape matching the park’s curved lines, give shape to these four public pavilions. The first leaf is solid, it shelters the essential functions: public toilets intended for residents and park visitors, park maintenance service offices and rest areas. The second leaf is light, it is at the same time a shade and an urban signal. In China, public toilets are omnipresent in the urban landscape, but they are often lacking architectural quality and they do not fit in well in the city. To approach this kind of buildings as a real architectural project, halfway between architecture and urban installation, means to recognize their place in the urban landscape and to acknowledge their importance for the community.

properties.nom_etablissement: BISMUT&BISMUT, Cartier, Geneva, Rue du Rhône 35, 1204 Genève, Suisse
properties.description_projet: The Cartier store in Geneva is Daniel and Michel Bismut’s first collab with the luxury brand. After New York, London and Paris, Geneva, another emblematic address in the history of Cartier boutiques around the world, lifts the veil on spaces that have been profoundly transformed. The vast architectural and decorative project has led to a real metamorphosis of the store, which enhances its assets and offers the House’s customers a new, even more rich and intense experience. Daniel and Michel designed the entire second floor as well as several pieces of furniture around the identity of the brand.

properties.nom_etablissement: AC/AL, Floating Garden, Prek Toal Village, Cambodge
properties.description_projet: In close collaboration with Prek Toal villagers and local association Osmose, we designed a demonstration vegetable garden (pilot project), which would make it possible to experiment with this specific aquaculture technique, using quantities of available water hyacinth: an invasive, nocive and surabondant aquatic plant. With about 40 square meters of cultivation on water hyacinth beds, this garden would also offer a collaborative and permanent place to make social interactions easier and to propose regular trainings, as well as passageways around the gardens to protect them from river currents and provide better working conditions for the villagers.

properties.nom_etablissement: Fermob, Fermob London, 391 King St, London W6 9NJ, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet:
Fermob, the market leader, has achieved 30 consecutive years of growth, and generates 48% of its turnover abroad. It started with metal furniture, and has grown to offer a more comprehensive range of furnishings for outdoor spaces. Hotel and catering industry customers, for whom Fermob has a special department, appreciate the quality of the products and services on offer, in particular the customisation options.

For major clients and projects, Fermob formed a “Special Contracts” department that has created exclusive collections for groups like McDonalds, Starbucks, and Veuve Clicquot.

properties.nom_etablissement: SENEQUIER DESIGNCLUB, L.A, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: A seat that reinterprets traditional woven straw chairs, a classic that resonates in our collective unconscious. Riviera skilfully blends tradition, new materials and methods to reflect on the identity of our production and our regions. Beyond style, it questions the coherence of scale and location of production, at a time when climate change and globalization threaten to wipe out cultural imprints. Made from digitally milled beech, the seat is hand-woven from mooring ropes, a nod to the seafaring spirit of the Mediterranean from which it springs. 8 Riviera chairs were added to the FRENCH MOBILIER NATIONAL collection in January 2023. Entirely made in France. They are distributed internationally by ''The invisible collection''.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO DE LAUBADÈRE, FRAGMENTS, Gg. Rajawali No.1B, Dauh Puri Klod, Kec. Denpasar Bar., Kota Denpasar, Bali 80114, Indonésie
properties.adresse: Gg. Rajawali No.1B, Dauh Puri Klod, Kec. Denpasar Bar., Kota Denpasar, Bali 80114, Indonésie
properties.description_projet: Flavia de Laubadère presents a unique work in collaboration with Manon Bouvier, straw marquetry artist, 'Meilleur Ouvrier de France' 2019. This black lacquer screen reveals a nocturnal landscape, an accumulation of bamboo canes. The white leaves shine under the moonlight in the dark. Three independent folded sides create modules that can be arranged as a couple, triptych or solo to harmonize a room and create intimate spaces.

properties.nom_etablissement: VINCENT POUJARDIEU, Yubiwa, Burgstraat 18, 9000 Gent, Belgique
properties.description_projet: This new collection focuses on the detour of materials - copper wire, brass wire and stainless steel wire - originally used in the metal braiding technique for industry. It's a special kind of French know-how for custom-made creations. The interweaving of copper, brass and stainless steel wires produces a complex composition of subtle contrasts, whose reflective texture captivates the eye and fascinates. The innovative and diverted use of this material (braided sheath) results in a robust superposition of interwoven geometric and organic curves inspired by the infinity knot (Tibetan) and nautical knots. The choice of shapes and materials that make up the works are at the origin of the symbolic expression of the endless cycle of life and the strong aesthetic value of this collection of sculptural pieces with haute couture finishes. Pieces in the collection: bench, chair (throne), table, coffee table, console and shelf. MATERIALS A heavy-duty stainless steel tubular structure, bent and welded, forms the overall shape of each piece. The tubular structure is covered by a custom-braided sheath made from a variety of metal wires, including copper, brass and stainless steel. TECHNIQUE All parts are manufactured in France. Our craftsmen and women are skilled in the techniques of metal braiding, tubular bending, assembly and welding.

properties.nom_etablissement: HALL HAUS, DKR, 12 avenue Georges Pompidou, Sénégal
properties.description_projet: Hall Haus wants to re-appropriate a classic piece of West African furniture, the Chaise à Palabre. This chair is a purely functional object used essentially as a comfort seat, thanks to its shape. This chair is culturally used for group meetings, exchanges and, above all, for TRANSMITTING. A value deeply rooted in this region of Africa. The idea of reinterpreting this chair in folded and perforated metal came to us through transmission. For us, this exercise is the link we're trying to create with our continent of origin, challenging an ancestral know-how and object and bringing it into other universes, notably the one we want to build between our suburbs here in France and our continent. The first prototype was made in Dakar, Senegal, and exhibited and sold at designer Bibi Seck's Quatorze Zero Huit gallery. Dimensions: 770 x 640 x 600 mm Materials: Poly zinc epoxy steel / Made in France

properties.nom_etablissement: HARTIS PARIS, Ossature, 315 Spring St, New York, NY 10013, États-Unis
properties.adresse: 315 Spring St, New York, NY 10013, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: Since April, Hartis has been presented by Objective Gallery in New York and Shanghai. In addition to bespoke objects regularly commissioned by the gallery for prestigious clients, furniture is on permanent display in the New York space. The Ossature armchair, emblematic of the Tour de Mains collection, made of solid oak hand-hammered by a Meilleur Ouvrier de France chair joiner. In New York, it is upholstered in Nathalie P. fabric, woven to order in France, near Valence, using locally sourced yarns. A piece of exceptional craftsmanship, combining beauty, comfort and precision.

properties.nom_etablissement: KIRA, DELTA207, Via della Spiga 32, Milan
properties.description_projet: The Tadashi table lamp impresses with its bold, clean lines. Its base is made up of Its base is made up of two solid blocks of wood, which form a solid base anchored to the ground. However, this double monolith is contrasted by the fragility and delicacy of the fastenings. Finally, the black lacquer and lacquered paper shade soften the overall effect by allowing the light to circulate. Materials: Ceramic and lacquered wood, Lacquered paper Dimensions: W.270 x D.270 x H.600

properties.nom_etablissement: LEO SENTOU, Riviera, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: The L.A Side Table by Leo Sentou is a reinterpretation of a “servante monopole” by eighteenth-century master cabinetmaker Louis Aubry (1741-1814). Forged entirely by hand in Europe, with a delicately textured finish, its sinuous lines project a strong sculptural presence, contrasting beautifully with a series of tabletops in a variety of materials. Alabaster, glass and lacquered wood: each with its distinctive textured characteristics, which, depending on choice, lend the piece an entirely different persona.

properties.nom_etablissement: MARTA BAKOWSKI DESIGN STUDIO, Triptyque, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: The 'FRAGMENTS' Collection was created during the 'ADIR _ French Design Meets Balinese Crafts' residency in collaboration with CushCush Gallery in Bali, Indonesia. It is composed of three pieces of furniture: A wardrobe ('Bali Night Sky'), a small cabinet ('Lamak') and a sideboard ('Lele'). The concept of the collection is that of the travel diary, this space of expression and personal narrative recounting the strong moments experienced in an 'elsewhere'. The drawing, the text, the image meet there in a free, hybrid and rarely linear form, thus offering an exploded and lively reading. During her research stay in Bali, the designer Marta Bakowski collected and inventoried many images, shapes, silhouettes, signs, colors, materials, patterns, words and typographies, thus creating a repertoire which enabled her to constitute a starting palette. . The collection is intended as a three-dimensional travel diary, a succession of Polaroids, fragments of memory that come to life on a family of three cabinets inspired by local architecture and 'Gerobak', these vehicles of itinerant merchants who populate the street markets. Designed as semi-open structures, partitioned by boxes and panels that welcome a story made of palm leaf marquetry as well as painting and wood carving, these cabinets are an ode to local know-how, with a French twist. . In her translation work, the designer played with languages, mixing elements of everyday life, folklore and popular traditions with elements from local religious beliefs and traditions, creating a new narrative. We thus find the sky of Bali, animated by colorful kites that encounter patterns inspired by offerings and textile patterns, or even these typical illustrations of street markets alongside animal representations from traditional 'Kamasan' paintings, flirting with letterings.

properties.nom_etablissement: RL STUDIO, KNOT, Eden House, Jumeirah Garden City - 41st St - Al Satwa - Dubai - Émirats arabes unis
properties.adresse: Eden House, Jumeirah Garden City - 41st St - Al Satwa - Dubai - Émirats arabes unis
properties.description_projet: This piece was realized for an exhibition in Antwerp with Atelier Ecru Gallery. It won the Wallpaper award for the best elements of surprises and is now sol and shipped internationally. Yubiwa is made from Marbled Salts and stands for ''ring'' in Japanese. Dimensions: 40x45cm and about 50kg

properties.nom_etablissement: ROBINSON FERREUX, Tadashi, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: With DELTA207 and DELTA117 lamp his intent was to evoke equilibrium, with simplicity and straightforward forms. Whilst observing these luminescent objects, multiple references to the esoteric, to the symbolic, to Ancient Egypt and to the Outer Space exploration, will be spotted by the attentive observer… Elements of the Myazaki’s world, of totems and sacred objects are also recalled. All of this merges into the word DELTA. DELTA follows up on the experimental approach of the designer, seeking for lightness. Paying homage to the Italian school of the 1950's and 1960's, modernist and minimalist at the time, and above all to the French sophistication, the designer’s passion for handmade objects is blatantly expressed through this collection.

properties.nom_etablissement: APPARTEMENT2, DIPLOPODA, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: Inspired by the shape of myriapod with a long rounded black shape, this new DIPLOPODA Collection was designed during the rainy season in Reunion Island. In the garden some millipedes go out, especially the “iule”.They are characterized by having two pairs of jointed legs. The use of noble and natural materials such as solid oak and travertine echoes these small animals which, despite their appearance, are extremely robust.

properties.nom_etablissement: ARNAUD LAPIERRE, Wing, 800 West Ave, Miami Beach, FL 33139, États-Unis
properties.adresse: 800 West Ave, Miami Beach, FL 33139, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: Designing an object that limits its carbon footprint while making the most of the material's properties? WING's aim is to limit its environmental impact right from the design stage: starting with a scrap metal reprocessing line, we laser-cut a silhouette from a sheet of steel that can be shaped into a volume: using the mechanical properties of the material to stiffen the structure and reveal a functional identity: following the contours of a LED tube and using it as a reflector. Once formed, the steel is then heated by hand with a torch, delicately like a paintbrush, controlling the spread of heat to produce a blue color, or a specific gradation. This natural finish eliminates the need for finishing and painting, giving the object a unique and varied personality. Heated blue? Heated blue is a surface color that ferrous metals take on at around 400 degrees Celsius. When a torch is passed torch, a chromatic spectrum appears around the main heating point, ranging from dark blue to violet to yellow. The blue heat tints the metal's scale and protects it from erosion, so the surface of the object requires no mechanical or chemical treatment to preserve its longevity, and offers a unique, iridescent color for each object produced without the use of lacquer, paint or varnish. Heated blue provides a gradation from yellow to pink to blue, the color difference being directly related to the time the metal is exposed to the heat. The higher the temperature, the darker the blue and then the gunmetal. The WING lamp is available in three versions: LASER, BEAM, and BLUE in satin, brushed or mirror finish. Distributed by AYBAR Miami USA. Four examples are in the Mobilier National collection.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER PIERRE-LOUIS GERLIER, Moucharabieh , 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: What the adult draws on his scale, the child transforms it on his own scale. An object for an adult can be transformed into a space for the child. Under the table is the ideal place to observe the world of adults who gather there to exchange, and make decisions. Moucharabieh, is an observation post where the child can observe and listen to the adult world without being seen. The legs of the table unfold to offer a cocoon where only the child can take refuge, hide and observe. A multitude of combinations are possible to create different spaces. The tabletop rests on two fixed legs in a circular arc. On these legs are fixed wings that can be unfolded to create spaces. The superposition of the arcs in perforated sheets and the mixture of colors create a kinetic game

properties.nom_etablissement: BERTRAND PINCEMIN DESIGNER, Specchio Four, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: Specchio Four is not only a mirror, but also a piece of furniture that interacts with the spaces in which it is installed, thanks to its composition of four points of view referring directly to its name. Specchio Four rethinks the viewer's experience of a mirror. Specchio Four is a 100% single-material work in polished stainless steel, based on a single sheet of metal bent into shape with welded connections at the corners. The bending techniques employed give the piece a high degree of rigidity despite the thinness of the metal sheet. The mirror has no real direction of installation, and can be installed on any of the four sides, depending on the space in which it is integrated and the chosen positioning. The wall fixings have been designed to make it easy to vary the direction of installation periodically, so as to renew experiences of interaction and discovery. With the Specchio Four, the designer's intentions are ultimately in line with his work as a scenographer, staging the viewer and the space, proposing a renewed play of reflections and scenes. The mirror has been presented and exhibited many times at international shows in London and Milano, and is now part of the Collection of the Cosmit Foundation (organizer of the Fiera del Mobile di Milano). In 2023, it entered the Collections of the Mobilier National Français. Dimensions 700 mm x 700 mm x 100 mm

properties.nom_etablissement: CARBONE 14, Torii, 2-4 Huntsworth Mews, London NW1 6DD, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: Acquisition of Mobilier National, 2023 470x1200x800 Beech, varnishes and paints Numbered table Torii is a coffee table inspired by a 19th century print by the Japanese painter Kawase Hasui. It has 3 trays of different sizes and heights carried by 6 feet. These are covered with 12 layers of paint from the painting. Over time, life and shocks, the feet will wear out and reveal the colors of the underlays. This wear, provided for in the design, makes the table unique and gives it, as time goes by, its singular value.

properties.nom_etablissement: FRÉDÉRIC SAULOU, Delta, 455 west 19th streetNew York, NY 10011
properties.description_projet: The first question that one could ask oneself in front of these works could be about the notion of balance or even volumetric understanding. Beyond the use, these four new pieces thus raise a technical and symbolic question announcing my creative reflection. Indeed, my work since 2013 tends to highlight the mineral materials from buildings and heritage to give them back their nobility, to question the territory around the material, know-how, in close connection with architecture and his history. For this new collection, I like to play on the dualities offered by the different properties of the materials used and their architectural uses, reflected in the tension and technicality between the colored, dense and heavy stone in balance with the transparent glass, thin and light. These singularities, often in opposition, therefore highlight the different attributes of each material and their use in the architectural landscape. They naturally tell a story between mineral matter, fragment of a territory or history and industrial matter transformed and brought back by man. Indeed, the pieces of stone used are scraps of semi-precious materials or forgotten architectural elements. They will be reshaped to be revealed and then sublimated by weightlessness. As for the glass, it comes from modern shaping associated with a cutting-edge technology on stone, a process developed in collaboration with Goude Glass. These two materials continue to cohabit and find themselves associated with the archetypal codes of contemporary architecture, between construction and graphic work. These materials will serve each other to be reborn, to rehabilitate. The subtle combination of materials is enhanced by discreet, even invisible means of attachment. The bonding, transparent and considerably resistant, allows the stone to be fixed to the glass without revealing any assembly system or hardware. However, manual skill was essential. The principle evokes the rehabilitation of an object, of a building by a new, added element which comes to (re)construct the object. The stones levitate as if by magic and graphically structure the whole, symbol of a strong architectural anchoring such as a contemporary renovation of materials and uses. Through this technical enigma, the works question the impact of man on matter and its environment, reconditioning as the empowerment of forms in contemporary architectural space, mastery of balance.

properties.nom_etablissement: A+A COOREN, 50 Lambs for a Coyote: A Tribute to Joseph Beuys, 693 5th Ave, New York, NY 10022, États-Unis
properties.titre_affiche: 50 Lambs for a Coyote: A Tribute to Joseph Beuys
properties.description_projet: 50 Lambs for a Coyote chair is handmade by Aki+Arnaud, developed to pay homage to the German artist, Joseph Beuys, in specific reference to his 1974 performance I Like America and America Likes Me. Aki+Arnaud's chairs convey the same respect for American Indian tribes expressed by Beuys in his original performance, as Aki+Arnaud's understanding of coherence with the natural world in high esteem. The chairs are made from felt and bee’s wax, two especially important materials to Beuys, as well as lamb skin leather that was discarded from the market, due to its non-uniform colour – incidentally, the exact quality that drew Aki+Arnaud to it.

properties.nom_etablissement: INDIA MAHDAVI, Réenchanter La Villa Médicis, Rome, Villa Medici, Viale della Trinità dei Monti, 1, 00187 Roma RM, Italie
properties.adresse: Villa Medici, Viale della Trinità dei Monti, 1, 00187 Roma RM, Italie
properties.description_projet: Located inside Villa Medici, a 16th-century villa on mount Pincio, the French Academy in Rome is a national public institution. Under the authority of the Ministry of Culture, it fulfills three complementary missions: to welcome artists, creators and art historians for residency programs to outline a cultural and artistic program that includes all fields of creation to make its architectural and landscape heritage, as well as its art collections, known to the public. India Mahdavi was invited to refurbish the piano nobile (first floor) overlooking the illustrious gardens – thus becoming the first woman to intervene inside these walls. The program for the piano nobile included two historical bedrooms, which were named after famous residents Claude Debussy and Galileo, to host important guests from the cultural world or sometimes rented out the Lili Boulanger salon, named after the first woman composer resident at the Villa, which displays Debussy’s original piano and finally the three connecting patrimonial rooms – opened to the public for daily visits – among which, in the center, the ‘Cardinal de Medici’ room. Depending on the usage of the different spaces, the project required varied approaches – from historical refurbishment to specific custom designed furniture, from interior design to creating a new function for the Lili Boulanger salon de musique, once an interstitial space. In the Debussy and Galileo bedrooms, Mahdavi imagined platform-raised beds inspired by those of the Renaissance, as depicted in paintings by Piero della Francesca, Fra Angelico or Filippo Lippi, to enjoy the most beautiful view overlooking Rome through the high windows. Both dressed in brightly colored wood marquetry according to classic Renaissance patterns with a distinctive palette for each room, they show an interesting contrast between past and present – conversing nicely with the Balthus patina walls and the Jacopo Zucchi frieze. The two patterns were applied on all custom pieces in these rooms, to identify Mahdavi’s intervention from the existing furniture, which was partly kept. In the Cardinal de Medici’s room – wich reveals the most beautiful ceiling depicting the astrological theme of the Cardinal – the existing bedroom furniture was replaced by a custom-designed rug which shape and form echo the garden outside, and which colors reflect the ceiling above, thus sky and ground are facing each other. The representation of a garden in a rug is also part of an ancient tradition in Iran, the birth country of the designer. This project challenged India Mahdavi to integrate the historical context in a respectful yet modern way, to converse with the heritage of the Villa in order to create a new chapter – to be humble and strong at the same time. Mahdavi focused on creating a human-centric experience by imagining new authentic moments that add to the visit experience – for instance she moved Debussy’s piano from one of the private guestrooms to the unoccupied vestibule, creating the Lili Boulanger salon de musique – in which fellows and residents are able to play at their convenience, and where guests and visitors can sit and enjoy the Visconti light under the auspices of Venus and Appolo. One of the ambitions of this project was to highlight French and Italian craftsmanship and know-hows through a selection of artisans and ateliers that have been identified as perpetuating a living patrimonial heritage. India Mahdavi and her studio were honored to work with outstanding manufacturing companies and craftsmen who maintain excellence in their field. In a non-exhaustive list, she entrusted Manufacture Robert Four (Aubusson tapestry) for the hand-tufted rug in the Cardinal de Medici’s room Italian textile manufacturer Dedar assisted her studio with printing the custom-pattern of the baldaquin fabric in the Galileo guestroom Creazioni Luciano crafted custom ceramic tiles for the Galileo and Debussy bathrooms in a traditional Italian cloisonné technique. Mahdavi says that this project also pushed the boundaries of some makers like Craman-Lagarde and Ateliers Michalon by challenging them to work with wood marquetry in a contemporary way. The guestrooms and patrimonial rooms were supplied with textiles and linens of the highest quality, with the support of Maison Pierre Frey, Manufacture Royale Bonvallet, Passementerie Verrier, Society Limonta and Tassinari & Chatel. As for the existing 17th-century Italian furniture – most of it was kept, restored and reupholstered, as one of the project ambitions was to give them a new life. And when in need of missing furniture, Mahdavi selected it from the Mobilier National, a major institution which keeps track of the institutional French furniture – and which, as one of the strongest partners of the project, opened its collections to Villa Medici, as a loan. Some contributors to this project intervened as patrons – which was the case of Mahdavi herself, but also the Bettencourt-Schueller Foundation which has focused on arts and crafts for over twenty years, and Maison Craman-Lagarde.

properties.nom_etablissement: MATALI CRASSET, Dark Sky (cielo Obscuro), Logroño, CONCENTRICO 08, LOGROÑO
properties.description_projet: An owl has landed in the middle of the city for Concentrico 08. On the one hand, as a totem animal, it symbolically guides us to see beyond the veil of deception, of illusion, and helps us to see what is usually kept hidden. On the other hand, it sees in the dark. In the heart of Logrono, the owl became space and has two temporalities: At night it wakes up, its eyes become luminous. A reassuring presence in the night, it calls from afar to come and a more temperate warmth and to settle down to look at the stars. This is particularly appreciated from the deckchairs - a sloping surface on either side of its nose. A work in defence of the starry sky, in danger of disappearing due to the multiplication of satellites. A work that summons the sensitivity and reaffirms that the sky is above all a space of imagination and freedom where everything is in eternal motion. The day, It is an almost maternal presence that invites intergenerational scenarios around three spaces that cohabit: a double tunnel for the joy of children who are invited to enter the owl's nose a double inclined plane which offers the possibility to lie down in an informal way a high plane, behind, which invites to settle down, to exchange and to look at life as through a visor. A space dedicated to eating with friends. A yellow metal structure that emphasizes the curved contours and a wooden covering that provides a warm interface for sitting. A work to be lived in, placed in the heart of the town of Logrono, which interacts with the Concha del Paseo, a bandstand in the form of an auditorium created in 1954 on the Paseo del Espolon.

properties.nom_etablissement: ULTRACONFIDENTIEL DESIGN, Tira Beauty, Mumbai, Mumbai, India
properties.description_projet: Launched by India’s largest retailer “Reliance Retail Limited”, Tira is an Omnichannel platform for cosmetics beauty products, which aims to break down barriers in the beauty space and democratize beauty for consumers across segments. “Our vision for the brand is to be the leading beauty destination for accessible yet aspirational beauty, one that is inclusive and one that harbours the mission of becoming the most loved beauty retailer in India”, says Isha Ambani, Executive Director at Reliance Retail Ventures Limited. Ultra-vision: embracing the differences The design vision of Ultraconfidentiel for Tira Headquarters starts from the roots and identity of the brand: a young and vibrant working culture, which cheers diversity and inclusivity. The space takes shape through organic lines and asymmetric geometries which represent self-acceptance and celebration of skin imperfections while the use of wall layers in different nude shades, symbolizes the complexity and the diversity of skin tones. Space features: flexibility is the key The workspace is bright and dynamic, with muted and soft pastel colours. The dedicated workstations are placed along the glazing, to ensure direct access to natural light, with a breath-taking view over Mumbai’s iconic Skyline. This is adjoined by open breakout and collaboration areas for spontaneous meetings and workshops, which can be flexibly used with different levels of privacy by using curtains. The cafeteria has a fresh and vibrant vibe, encouraging its use not only over lunch time but also extending into the breakout and collaboration zones present on the floor. It also creates a natural filter between the working area and the photo-shooting and editing zone, which takes shape in an open, fluid and flexible space. Curved and suspended rail curtains run throughout the zone, creating functional and flexible spaces as per the users’ needs, ranging from recreational areas, shooting bays and fitting rooms to make-up stations.

properties.nom_etablissement: MOINARD BETAILLE, Cartier Genève, Rue du Rhône 35. 1204 Genève GE. CH. Suisse
properties.adresse: Rue du Rhône 35. 1204 Genève GE. CH. Suisse
properties.description_projet: Situated at the southern tip of Lake Geneva, the boutique is set at the foot of a magnificent listed building dating from the 1960s, to which the renovation has restored its original appearance. On the façade, the numerous sets of screens create a subtle link between the street and the boutique. As soon as you enter, the Cartier identity comes together with all the contrasts that Geneva has to offer: the peace of the lake that borders the street, the power of the snow-capped Alps and the tranquillity of the green plains that stretch across their foothills. Everything comes together in harmony, giving the project a unique character. The floor, inspired by the motif of a Cartier jewel, unfurls and glows, like a sunrise over the lake. You're walking on a treasure trove of light. As with all Moinard Bétaille projects, this entirely redesigned space gives pride of place to craftsmanship: light and shade, materials and colours are skilfully balanced to create a veritable jewellery box. The omnipresent gold reinforces the preciousness and uniqueness of this place.

properties.nom_etablissement: BISMUT&BISMUT, Yacht Sd118, VIARREGIO ITALY
properties.description_projet: The SD118 is Daniel and Michel Bismut’s second collab for the boatyard. It was nominated for « Best Yacht » in its category in 2022. San Lorenzo Yacht was born from a desire to break with usual yachting codes by introducing a feeling of comfortable luxury. Daniel and Michel imagined this yacht as a sophisticated beach hut with particular attention to textures and colors. The sophistication of the design replaces ostentation thanks to the use of bright colors and warm curves, but also elements inspired by nature: mat wooden floors, white ceilings with a discreet pattern inspired by fish scales, or even wooden wall paneling, textured as if floating in the sea.

properties.nom_etablissement: PIERRE GONALONS, Giudecca, Venice, Ile de la Giudecca, Venise, Italie
properties.adresse: Ile de la Giudecca, Venise, Italie
properties.description_projet: VENETIAN BUBBLE Apart from her desire for a large open space, the owner of this Venetian pied-à-terre gave few instructions to designer and decorator Pierre Gonalons. A carte blanche he relished, punctuating the space with solid and hollowed-out circles from floor to ceiling. For me, Venice is not a city like any other. I own hundreds of books on its history, I take vacations on the Lido island and I regularly take part in heritage tours of its monuments,' confides Pierre Gonalons. Who better to renovate this pied-à-terre on the top floor of a former palace on the Giudecca? Like an echo of the lagoon's reflections, the kitchen features green-veined marble, the 'King Sun' suspension over the dining table is made of Murano glass, while the headboard is upholstered in a fabric produced by Fortuny, whose factory is just a few hundred meters away. As for the pink-tinted glass chosen for the balustrade of the staircase and walkway. LIGHT AND OPEN SPACE, THE PERFECT EQUATION TO SUBLIMATE A TOP FLOOR The design is inspired by the one used for the Serenissima's lampposts. The walkway in question, which serves the guest bedroom nestled on the mezzanine, is the strong architectural gesture of the apartment, which the owner wanted to be as open as possible. As she points out: 'What I find remarkable about Pierre is that his work is contemporary and at the same time very referential. Hence the constant mix of contemporary furniture and older pieces. It was also decided to preserve the old kitchen's terrazzo floor, despite its irregular shape. The lady of the house wanted to keep a trace of the past, and she didn't need to insist,' says the decorator with a smile. It's an approach I love. What's more, the terrazzo pattern is identical to that of the legendary Olivetti boutique in Piazza San Marco, designed by architect Carlo Scarpa. Another Venetian tribute! THE GEOMETRIC LOUNGE Squaring the circle. A recurring motif in Pierre Gonalons' work, the round struts its stuff on the 'See through' sofa and armchair designed for Italian publisher Paradisoterrestre and upholstered in 'Cyclades' linen (Métaphores). Their curves contrast with the rectilinear forms of the beams and architectural structure of the apartment. A series of walnut shelves made by a local carpenter. SPARKLING PALETTE The salon's scenography was inspired by a set designed by Pierre Gonalons for an exhibition at the Hôtel de Soubise in Paris in 2020, where he married chairs from the 'See through' collection with his hand-sculpted wool 'Palette' rug. 'Pierre has a gift for mixing colors,' says the owner. Her opinion is confirmed by this bright and cheerful setting. On the wall, charcoal by Hilton McConnico. Lacquered coffee table. FLUIDITY IN THE AIR Previously divided into a multitude of small rooms, the space has been decompartmentalized to create a large living room flooded with light, enhanced by a light oak floor. In the background, the oil on canvas 'Happily Ever After' by Parisian painter Pierre Seinturier has been hung in line with the dining table. VANISHING LINES IN THE DINING ROOM The dining area is lit by the 'King Sun Murano' suspension created by Pierre Gonalons using a speckled glass technique developed by Stories of Italy. idealbord' table in birch, rosewood and steel, designed by Otto Wretling circa 1936, and vintage chairs by Georges Candilis and Anja Blomstedt. The multicolored vase (Venini) comes from one of publisher Giobagnara's four Venetian boutiques. INTERIOR DESIGN: THINK PINK... AND GREEN TOO Powdery tones dominate the kitchen area, where the original terrazzo floor has been preserved. Credenza and worktop in Verde Mediterraneo marble, custom-made lacquered wood furniture and stove. On the shelf, a duo of decanters by Hilton McConnico for Daum crystalware sits alongside a series of plates from the 1930s with cubist motifs (Richard Ginori). King Sun Murano' hanging lamp (Pierre Gonalons). SUNSET IN THE BEDROOM Covered in 'Uccelli' fabric (Fortuny) in antique yellow, the rounded headboard brings a touch of softness to the master bedroom. The sunny motifs of the 'King Sun' bed linen designed by Pierre Gonalons (Vis-à-Vis Paris) are inspired by the ironwork of the Château de Versailles. Vintage cashmere throw. The bamboo 'Karumi' stool (Hermès) doubles as a bedside table. THE BALUSTRADE, PUNCTUATED BY CIRCULAR OPENINGS, DRAMATIZES THE DECOR ON BOTH LEVELS - A GRAPHIC GESTURE. With its balustrade of lacquered wood and tinted glass, the walkway serving the mezzanine also serves to dramatize the space. Its circular openings are reminiscent of ship portholes, adding a maritime touch. A last tribute to the port of Venice.

properties.nom_etablissement: CHZON, Gran Hotel Montesol, Ibiza, Passeig De Vara De Rey - Ibiza - Balearic Islands - Spain
properties.adresse: Passeig De Vara De Rey - Ibiza - Balearic Islands - Spain
properties.description_projet: After Renovating The Restaurant Sabbaba + Rooftop In 2021, We Have Renovated The Rooms Of This Mythical Hotel Of Ibiza, The First Opened On The Island. The Neocolonial Building From 1933 Is Made Of Columns, Pediments And Arches, Painted In Pale Yellow And White. The Color Palette We Have Developed For The Interior Design Uses The Pale Yellow Of The Outside, But According To The Ayurvedic Principles, We Tried Cooling, Calming Colours Inside The Hotel To Counterbalance Heat Outside. Solar Colors In Common Areas, Lunar Colors In Rooms, Favoring The Colors Of White, Blue, Grey, Light Green And Pastel Hues. We Have Played With The Bohemian Side Of Ibiza, Using A Lot Of Fabrics, Patterns, Fringes, Pompom. We Have Mixed Those With Light Wood, Colorful Rugs And Very Textured Walls. We Have Created Especially For The Hotel A Shell Texture On Walls, By Hand Pressing Seashells Into The Lime To Shape It, One By One. The Hotel Is Very Colorful To Reflect The Joy And Tolerance Of Ibiza, And We Have Also Used Some Cosmic Shapes And Winks : In Every Room, There Is A Huge Moon Carved In The Wall, To Create An Opening Between The Room And The Bathroom. We Have Drawn Some Iron Chairs, With A Moon Pattern. Brass Sun On The Wall, A Lot Of Wavy Lines Too, Masks Handmade By Anna Alexandra In Mallorca, Playdough Stool From Diego Faivre. Tiles Are Also Important In This Hotel : We Have Used Some Traditional Zelliges To Cover The Niches Of The Mini Bar : Orange, Brown, Off White. The Wardrobe's Doors Close Thanks To Jigsaw Puzzle's Shape, With A Very Glossy Lacquer On Top. Bathroom Vanities Are Made From Lava In France, With Large Shaped Mirrors In Walnut And Lacquer, Plus Of Course Small Pompoms.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER YOKYOK, The Chords, Oslo, Hoymagasinet, Oslo, Norvège
properties.description_projet: The Chords is a temporary installation designed for the Oslo Freedom Forum opening at Hoymagasinet in Norway. HRF and Moonageevents invited YokYok to think and design an In-situ installation for this singular space. The challenge was to create an installation acting as a canvas for the night: the cocktail, the fashion show and then the party. YokYok proposed to tense lights threads of wool above the assembly using the existing structure for an economy of means. The tense wool links both sides of the barn together. «The Chords» evokes links of solidarity between people and resonates with Human Rights Foundation’s purpose.

properties.nom_etablissement: LINA GHOTMEH — ARCHITECTURE, 22nd Serpentine Pavilion 2023, London, London W2 3XA, Royaume-Uni
properties.description_projet: A table is an invitation to dwell together, in the same space and around the same table. It is an encouragement to enter into a dialogue, to convene and to think about how we could reinstate and re-establish our relationship to nature and the Earth. In today’s changing times, this Pavilion offers a celebratory space. It is endowed with a table, around which we will sit together in a modest, low structure and in an atmosphere reminiscent of Toguna huts of the Dogon people in Mali, West Africa, designed to bring all members of a community together in discussion. Here we can eat, work, play, meet, talk, rethink, and decide. Built with bio-sourced and low-carbon materials, the structure appears like a skeleton. Sustainably sourced timber ribs are arranged to support a suspended pleated roof. Echoing the structures of tree leaves, the Pavilion embraces the nature of the park in which it emerges. Reminding us of the many lives blossoming beneath our feet, the concave lines of its perimeter are drawn from the forms in the stems and canopies of adjacent trees. While rooted in its place and welcoming the space of the park with its open gallery-like envelope, the Pavilion grows as an adaptable system. It can be disassembled and reassembled, allowing it to live beyond its Serpentine site, while holding the memory of its original ground.

properties.nom_etablissement: TRISTAN AUER, Royal Belmond Scotsman, Train Royal Scotsman
properties.description_projet: March 2023 – Today, Royal Scotsman, A Belmond Train, Scotland announces the launch of two new Grand Suites set to join the rake in May 2024. Mirroring the look and feel of a luxury country house, the Grand Suites elevate the onboard experience by providing the ultimate setting for a cinematic Scottish escapade. The new suites will take the train’s accommodation categories to four: Grand Suites, Double, Twin and Single cabins. SUBLIME BY DESIGN: A REFLECTION OF SCOTLAND’S EPHEMERAL LANDSCAPE The spacious Grand Suites brim with elegant references to Scottish culture and its outstanding natural beauty. Interiors take inspiration from the destination through the hues of green, grey, beige and blue used for the handcrafted wall-covering, upholstery and furniture, which reflect the tones of the surrounding landscape. Local materials like stone and wood are abundantly used in the lavish ensuite bathrooms, while decorative patterns echo Edwardian flair, Pictish stones motifs and Celtic symbolism, all artfully designed by Tristan Auer. Enveloping dark wooden wall panelling embellished with intricate marquetry form the backdrop for a double bed with embossed bedhead, dressing table with stool, Scottish larch dining table, and places to relax on a sumptuous sofa and armchair. Guests of the Grand Suites will also benefit from private transfers and a rejuvenating treatment in the train’s moving spa - the only one of its kind in Europe. AN ELEVATED EXPERIENCE OF SCOTLAND IN MOTION The Royal Scotsman offers an all-encompassing experience of the Highlands with its two-to seven-night selection of themed journeys, all leaving and returning to Edinburgh Waverley station. Guests are invited to embrace the sophisticated camaraderie spirit, as they enjoy on board dining with their fellow travellers in the two wood panelled dining cars, and live entertainment throughout the stay. .

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO ADRIEN GARDÈRE, Tales Of A Connected World, Lusail, 7GVV+P9Q Near Museum of Islamic Art, Doha, Qatar
properties.titre_affiche: Tales Of A Connected World, Lusail
properties.adresse: 7GVV+P9Q Near Museum of Islamic Art, Doha, Qatar
properties.description_projet: Taking place in the heart of Doha, Studio Adrien Gardère is designing the exhibition that will be the precursor of the future Lusail Museum, designed by Swiss architects Herzog & de Meuron. The exhibition features an important Orientalist collection of paintings, sculptures, decorative arts and photographs from Antiquity to the present day. The scenography unfolds two vast open spaces that enter into dialogue with successive, more intimate and colourful rooms. Counterpoints, interplay of views and transversality between the works have guided the design to affirm the ideas of exchange and encounters between civilisations. The spatial and radiating distribution of the artefacts offers multiple points of view, thus inviting visitors to develop their own reading of the exhibition, and ultimately of human relations across time and space. Video : ...Learn more

properties.nom_etablissement: TRICOIRE DESIGN STUDIO, Doha Gardens, Place Vendôme, Qatar
properties.description_projet: Architectural and scenographic creation for Hermès'store opening party To inaugurate the new Hermès'store in Doha, Qatar, Hermès wished to highlight Alexis Tricoire's universe, committed to sustainable development. His proposal was to create an unexpected 2000m2 organic shape architecture with a succession of woven bamboo caves. He brought life with his biomimetic creations based on recycled industrial materials, in continuity with his previous works made in iconic places. This setup, in front of the Persic Golf, gave the opportunity to Tricoire Design studio to share again his message beyond the europeens borders about the significance of recycling for nature's preservation.

properties.nom_etablissement: CONSTANCE GUISSET STUDIO, Solaire Culture, Tokyo, Los Angeles & London, Tokyo
properties.titre_affiche: Solaire Culture, Tokyo, Los Angeles & London
properties.description_projet: The scenography invites visitors to plunge into the solaire aura of Veuve Clicquot. Starting with the exhibition’s reception area, it spreads a warm ambiance through nuanced lighting and softly curved walls. The question of color was central, and we worked on it very precisely with the graphic designers of gr20 in order to reflect the happy and radiant aspect of the House. As the visitor moves through the exhibition, they absorb the history and the heritage of the House in an itinerary that celebrates the visionary character of Madame Clicquot and gives an important place to the artists she has inspired. Immersive moments convey all the atmosphere of Veuve Clicquot's legendary places, from the vertical crayères to sunrise over the vines of Champagne. As the visit continues, there are many surprises, including the arrival at a beach glistening with amber reflections, evoking holidays on the Riviera. This space was designed like a theatrical set to display some of the House’s treasured objects. Under the changing light of the sun, a long bar also serves as a display plinth for several pieces. Next, total installations invite our visitors on a cultural voyage. In an interactive library, they can listen to extracts of books while comfortably seated on a sofa. A playlist dedicated to the sun plays in a listening salon fueled by solar power. The visit ends with the boutique-restaurant, for a final, festive souvenir.

properties.nom_etablissement: WILMOTTE & ASSOCIÉS ARCHITECTES, United Nations House, Senegal, 1er Arrondissement, Pôle Urbain de Diamniadio SENEGAL
properties.adresse: 1er Arrondissement, Pôle Urbain de Diamniadio SENEGAL
properties.description_projet: Located in the heart of Diamniadio, on a 12.75-hectare site, the United Nations House brings together on a single site and within an iconic building the 34 agencies, funds and programmes of the United Nations System already present in Senegal, some of which are regional or sub-regional representations covering several countries. The aim of this ambitious project is to provide the United Nations system with a tool for working in a cohesive and coherent manner to improve collaboration in support of the people of Senegal and West Africa, within a secure framework that complies with all the requirements laid down by the United Nations. The challenge of this emblematic building is to illustrate the unity of the agencies, but also their independence and their influence on a national and regional scale. Eco-responsible and sustainable, the project is reminiscent of a water wheel, symbolising the influence of the institution across the region and the convergence of expertise. This large white circular volume unfurls seven wings of equal size, opening out onto the city and organising a new central space on a controlled scale. This centre is designed as a unifying void that accommodates the official functions as well as a vast public agora. Around the perimeter, the office floors are curved and open, preserving the independence of the agencies while encouraging synergy between them. The spatial organisation of the programme echoes the form: the official spaces are located right at the heart of the building: the amphitheatre and reception areas will host international conferences, seminars and debates. This central activity will be supported by a ring of public and shared spaces such as IT support, consultation centres, meeting points, catering areas, etc. Connected to the shared circle, the agencies, the UN's forces for action, take their place in the spokes, symbolising the dissemination of the UN's values. The surrounding landscape provides the link between this unusual form and the urban plan.
