By using local materials for the soil and vegetation, the garden will create a link between the local soil and the international sphere. The project is organised into four sectors necessary for the smooth running of the branches: -Service sector: 1,840 workstations / 37,270 m² SU -Public sector: training, documentation centre and workshops / 3,810 m² SU -Official sector: reception and conference / 3,430 m² SU -Support functions: catering, conviviality, services and logistics / 12,380 m² SU For a total workforce of 2,245 people.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER DONATIEN CARRATIER, Park Hyatt Maldives, Maldives
properties.description_projet: A creation of 895 sqm with panoramic views of the Indian Ocean our residence features 16-meter long freshwater infinity pool and three bedrooms with air-conditioned bathrooms to comfortably accommodate up to six guests. The extended private infinity pool terrace features sunken loungers and a shaded outdoor dining and lounge area, while separate decks adjoin the master and king bedrooms. Enjoy the comforts of home in this contemporary overwater retreat where soft furnishings of light brown and aquamarine combine with state-of-the-art room control features for a blissful ambiance. Expansive floor-to-ceiling windows fill the spacious living and dining area with warm light and serene ocean views. With direct access to the lagoon house reef, enjoy the best in overwater living and underwater explorations

properties.nom_etablissement: JAKOB+MACFARLANE, New Campus Of The French University Of Egypt, Cairo, Université Française d’Egypte, 21 Ismailia Desert Road Ville Shorouk, Le Caire, Egypte
properties.titre_affiche: New Campus Of The French University Of Egypt, Cairo
properties.adresse: Université Française d’Egypte, 21 Ismailia Desert Road Ville Shorouk, Le Caire, Egypte
properties.description_projet: Founded in 2002, the French University of Egypt (UFE) is located in El Shorouk, a city in the Greater Cairo area that is home to numerous schools and universities. Its current premises were insufficiently adapted for a growing population of students, therefore the UFE and the Agence Française de Développement have put in place a programme for developing a new 24.500 m2 campus aiming to accommodate 3000 students by 2025, and 7000 in the 2nd phase. Among the project's key objectives was the creation of a campus that would be exemplary in terms of environmental innovation and serve as a cultural showcase of Franco-Egyptian partnership. The future campus of the UFE is imagined first and foremost as an oasis - a haven for learning, a place of cooling shade protected by a sun-shading roof. Recessed gardens arranged between the buildings will use plants that can thrive in extremely dry environments their irrigation will be enabled by the grey water treatment system. A grid-shaped pergola roof in aluminium and steel will create shadow for buildings and circulation spaces. It will also incorporate an array of solar panels to cover on-site energy needs. The Auditorium, the Learning Center, as well as recreation spaces and cafeterias will frame the central square. The Auditorium will stand out for its brickwork envelope shaped into an organic form. Architecturally and functionally, our intention is to create a campus open to the city, a project that will serve as an ambassador of the two cultures. We imagine an inspiring, friendly and efficient environment for the faculty and students, but also an integrated part of the neighbourhood, a place that will hold value for the surrounding community. A number of the campus facilities will be made available for public use. The project will use locally sourced building materials such as the clay bricks, the principal material for the facades. Earthen construction will also be used. Digital technologies will act as a bridge between traditional techniques and contemporary architectural solutions. The topography of gardens recessed into the ground will facilitate water retention. These gardens will form a series of amphitheatre-shaped spaces with a pleasant microclimate - an outdoor extension of the classrooms, places for exchange and reflection, to be enjoyed in the mornings and evenings. An aquaponic greenhouse will allow for considerable savings in water consumption. Multidisciplinary design team : Architect : JAKOB+MACFARLANE Partner architect : RMC Engineering : ARTELIA Landscape architects: SEMPERVIRENS Acoustics : Jean-Paul Lamoureux

properties.nom_etablissement: STÉPHANE PARMENTIER, London Penthouse, London
properties.description_projet: Penthouse located in Battersea at the 12th and last floor, with a 500m² terrace. For the project we have played a lot with textures (Palm wood, brushed stones, ebony, patinated walls, suede, parchement and leather, etc...) and Art in this project. We have beautiful and strong artists such as Thomas Houseago, Jason Martin, Dadamaino, Robert Mappelthorpe, Antony Gormley, Jacques Adnet, Jean Royère, Pierre Szekely, Paavo Tynell, David Shirgley, Angelo Mangiarotti, Pierre Jeanneret, Luciano Fontana and some 17th century Japanese art pieces and armor.

properties.nom_etablissement: NATHAN LITERA, Chateau Royal, Bruxelles, PARC ROYAL LAEKEN BRUXELLES
properties.description_projet: Exterior and interior renovation of the Chateau Royal in the Parc de Laeken in Brussels. The castle was renovated by borrowing from the codes of classical architecture for the modifications and treatment of the exterior facades. While the interiors refer to the Empire and Napoleon style for its woodwork, marblework and its various floor layouts. Many craftsmen using ancestral techniques have been requisitioned to breathe new life into this prestigious residence, echoing the French way of life. During the final delivery of the site, the project received the congratulations of the Royal Donation of Belgium, in charge of the preservation of the various national and royal buildings and monuments.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO MHNA, Sofitel Marrakech Palais Impérial, Rue Haroun Errachid - Quartier Hivernage, L’Hivernage, 40 000 Marrakech, Maroc
properties.adresse: Rue Haroun Errachid - Quartier Hivernage, L’Hivernage, 40 000 Marrakech, Maroc
properties.description_projet: The palace draws its inspiration from the legends, the lights and the guests of the city of Marrakech. In order to respond to the refinement of Moroccan culture, Studio MHNA wanted to bring a very 'couture' attention to the decoration, in homage to a certain French couturier who fell in love with the red city .... As soon as you enter, the visitor is captivated by the discovery of two 'majlis', literally 'the place where one sits', intimately enclosed by metal screens whose pattern is reminiscent of lace. The black canvas seats and cushions are enriched with cord embroidery. The tables and lighting fixtures are also creations of Studio MHNA, which has combined marble, nickel silver and mirror to create a modern and contemporary style.

properties.nom_etablissement: VIEWPORT STUDIO, Virgin Galactic Spaceport, New Mexico, Co Rd A021, Truth or Consequences, NM 87901, United States
properties.adresse: Co Rd A021, Truth or Consequences, NM 87901, United States
properties.description_projet: What is the starting point for something that has never been designed before? Virgin Galactic – the company launching commercial space flights for tourists – selected us to curate a combined customer and employee experience alongside a completely bespoke interior design for the public-facing spaces and the operations centre of Spaceport America in the New Mexico desert. Our history of delivering award winning design for the Virgin Group stretches back nearly two decades which has given us an in-depth understanding of their brand DNA. Our starting point was the location of the spaceport and its surrounding landscape. Our team stood on the runway at Spaceport America and stared out to the New Mexico desert which is a stark and beautiful place, rich in colour and texture. This inspiration became the main influence for the design work that followed.

properties.nom_etablissement: ATELIER DU PONT, Son Alberti, Minorca, Cami de Binifamis - 07730 ALAIOR, MENORCA
properties.description_projet: Nestled among olive groves and the island's rocky terrain, an old building with lime and stone walls once housed a rustic farmhouse. The new owners discovered it in a state of disrepair and entrusted Atelier du Pont with the task of transforming it into their ideal vacation home. The french studio brings all of its aesthetics and know how to the table. Welcome to a typical Mediterranean setting. White lime is omnipresent throughout. It reflects the light and brightens the high interior rooms, which are not a lot open to the outside. Without touching the main structure, the architectural language of the house is redefined and enhanced, combining traditional influences with contemporary accents. Color was used to restructure and delineate these large spaces. A palette of warm, contrasting hues meets white walls and ceilings. This creative project boldly twists local architectural codes into a new chromatic universe. It showcases Menorcan craftsmanship and adds character and authenticity to the house. Most of the furniture is masonry, blending seamlessly with the architecture. Natural mineral materials are used, such as earthen concrete and earthenware. A little further down the grounds, a swimming pool protected by typical sandstone walls forms a little corner of paradise. A sense of calm and serenity reigns here. As if time had suspended its flight over the estate.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO RAZAVI ARCHITECTURE, Soho Triplex, New York, New York, NY
properties.description_projet: The project brief was to connect three existing but separate floors to create a single family home with rooftop & terrace access. To build a home – a place where people can sense each other’s presence – we opted to sacrifice floor area. Two separate floor openings were created, one in the intermediate slab, another one through all floors for the stairs. A large bronze finished helix which acts as the house’s central core. This contributed in creating a feeling of generosity on an otherwise modest floor plate, becoming a remarkable architectural feature by itself. Because a specific effort was made to design exquisite details, a sense of variety was created, enhanced by a beautifully crafted ensemble of daily life architectural and domestic objects, complemented by both custom designed furniture pieces and a selection of mid-century and contemporary designers. A material palette comprising walnut, marble, glass, steel, bronze and finely woven fabrics elevates the experience and offers different sensations based on which side of the building they are and time of the day. The large street facing arch was restored to its initial intended glory with a single pane of glass encased in a steel structure. Site specific artworks and others from the clients’ collection complete and further enhance the spatial experience but more importantly contribute to making this project a home.

properties.nom_etablissement: HUMBERT & POYET, Beefbar Milan, Corso Venezia, 11, 20121 Milano MI, Italie
properties.description_projet: In the historic and vibrant heart of Milan, the Beefbar restaurant has taken over the chapel of the Former Archiepiscopal Seminary. Inspired by the major figures of the Milanese style of the 40s and 60s, the interior designers and architects Emil Humbert and Christophe Poyet have masterfully transcended this place while respecting its memory and architectural details. Under a spectacularly high nave, interposed by dramatically sober vaults, the open kitchen, bar, and restaurant are seamlessly connected. They are united by the same terrazzo floor - mixing shades of green, black, white, and burgundy - whose stylized wave pattern pays tribute to the architect Luigi Caccia Dominioni. Half-height wood paneling in dark walnut recalls the aesthetic codes of Milanese cafés and provides a sense of comfort. Theatrically decorated, they are punctuated by triptych sconces by designer Ignazio Gardella and an eclectic collection of artworks in a variety of styles and subjects. Verde Alpi marble tables and chairs by Vico Magistretti furnish the space with elegance, combined with several suspended Asterios lamps in bronze and frosted glass, designed by the duo HUMBERT&POYET. Located in Piazza del Quadrilatero, just a stone’s throw from San Babila, Beefbar Milan resonates with this creative city, which has always been a city of opera, fashion and of course design. The restaurant reveals the inimitable sensuality and relaxed nature of the Italian spirit.

properties.nom_etablissement: RDAI, Maison Hermès Madison, New York, 706 Madison Avenue, NY 10065 New York
properties.description_projet: The Hermès Madison Avenue flagship store is a union of New York dynamism and Parisian elegance, and an ambitious fusion of three existing buildings. The historical 706 Madison Bank building plan offers a deep perspective, a very straight geometry, rhythmed with a sequence of small rooms. In contrast, 704 Madison - a combination of two town houses - features voluptuous curves and smooth lines a more organic architecture in tone and form, with multiple and inverted arches. We worked to reinforce this contrast and complementarity of atmosphere which runs throughout 706 and 704 enabling their histories to communicate with each other and allowing the public to discover their identities. The interiors explore, without any nostalgia and with a resolutely modern approach, an expression of what “Art deco” could be today, taking subtle cues from the New York Art Deco influence of the early Manhattan Rockefeller and Chrysler skyscrapers with a strong echo to Paris Art Deco periods. The interiors develop in a harmonious style, inspiration from nature, strong geometry and an extensive range of materials and colors such as green straw marquetry wall panels in the men’s department and equestrian, realized with French decorative artist by Lison de Caunes, gold crackled lacquer wall finish in the perfume department alcoves and celadon green crackled lacquer wall finish in the leather salon both realized by Atelier Maury, the bespoke oyster mushroom fabric covering the jewelry department and private jewelry salon wall walls , which were developed with Grethe Sorensen, Danish textile designer and recycled leather finish wall panels in the men’s VIP salon. The color palettes intensify from floor to floor with tones of green, dark chocolate and cognac on the Bank building side and warm neutrals – ivories, beiges, light browns – ochre and dusty pinks at 704 Madison. Decorative details were emphasized and translated into contemporary details such as the “trompe l’oeil” effect of the marble mosaic floor, the wooden coffered ceiling, and the grills of the original bank building’s safe. The Hermès atmosphere was strengthened with references to details from the original Hermes Faubourg, Paris 1926, including the leather glass showcases, oval glass and brass counters, or the Faubourg mosaic floor pattern. The staircase geometry provides an easy, fluid “promenade” from floor to floor. Organic, curved shapes were expressed in solid and perennial materials, resulting in a high-tech monolithic block stone staircase, with a sense of movement and lightness! The stone stair flights are built with a post tensioning technique, and the guardrails are double beam stone balustrades. A stair that floats upwards. The roof of the 704 building was re-built (providing a double height volume on the fourth floor), with a domelike double curved glass skylight, providing a very luminous atmosphere, which overlooks a lush roof garden designed in collaboration with Miranda Brooks. Once again, we find nature, curvaceous and smooth geometry, and fine details through an expansive glass-fiber bas-relief drawn by the French artist Francois Houtin with the representation of a dense nature turning around the room. The fourth floor welcomes the visitors with a bar, a speak easy and a promenade in the garden. This is a new era of retail where the client is invited to experience the lifestyle of the Maison Hermès.

properties.nom_etablissement: D'ISTRIA STUDIO, Hôtâ Hotel, Saint-imier, Hôtâ Hôtel  30 Rue du Vallon 2610 Saint Imier  Suisse
properties.adresse: Hôtâ Hôtel  30 Rue du Vallon 2610 Saint Imier  Suisse
properties.description_projet: The Hôtâ Hotel in Saint-Imier is an innovative project that pushes the boundaries of traditional hotel design. Nestled in the heart of the Bernese Jura mountains, this charming hotel offers 2 and 4-stars rooms and is inspired by the renowned watchmaking expertise of this region. The design thus harmoniously combines watchmaking aesthetics and an atmosphere of understated luxury. Whether it is the design of the lobby, from the 2-stars rooms with elegant finishes to the 4-stars rooms offering superior comfort and refinement, this project highlights the timeless elegance and attention to detail that characterize local watchmaking. The d'Istria Studio is very pleased to support the Swiss brand Hôtâ Hôtel in the development and implementation of this ambitious and innovative hotel concept.

properties.nom_etablissement: MAISON NUMÉRO 20, Dox Restaurant & Bar, Hyatt Regency Dusseldorf, Speditionstraße 19, 40221 Düsseldorf, Allemagne
properties.titre_affiche: Dox Restaurant & Bar, Hyatt Regency Dusseldorf
properties.description_projet: A true feast for the senses, DOX serves up an exquisite culinary experience with a side of stunning views of the Rhine thanks to the redesign by Oscar Lucien Ono. With its neo-brasserie elements and Franco-American fusion menu, the Dox Restaurant & Bar boasts a stunning view of the Rhine, giving the hotel the appearance of a massive cruise ship facing Frank Gehry's modern and cubical building. Taking inspiration from the luxurious first-class experience of transatlantic voyages from the 1920s, Ono's redesign is a tribute to the opulence and grandeur of that era. Varnished wood, marble, velvet, and cane form a striking combination, while fabrics from renowned publishers like Jab, Lelièvre, and Nobilis showcase rich hues of gold, orange-red, copper, brown, and bronze. Adding to the allure are the art deco-inspired geometric designs, lush botanical patterns, and fierce panther motifs that imbue the decor with refinement and power. The result is a sophisticated and timeless décor that effortlessly blends Art Deco design elements with contemporary touches, creating a glamorous and inviting atmosphere. The majestic bar, with its polished wooden liquor organ that resembles a perfume organ, features large velvet and brass stools where guests can relax and enjoy signature cocktails. During the summer, the glass walls open up, blurring the line between indoors and outdoors and enhancing the water-inspired atmosphere. The restaurant's décor is a stunning fusion of straw marquetry, gilding, bronze, and Murano glass, accentuated by a touch of panther carpeting, all seamlessly integrated to create a harmonious ambiance. The masterful combination of varnished wood, marble, velvet, and cane in gold, orange-red, copper, brown, and bronze hues exudes a sense of refined contrast and elegance. For a more intimate experience, the champagne lounge was designed to indulge guests in a luxurious hideaway filled with cozy nooks that magically appear through a combination of lattice and luminous screens. The lounge is designed with mirrors and rosewood and features a large bronze structure resembling an oversized champagne bowl topped with a pendant light that subtly evokes champagne bubbles.

properties.nom_etablissement: STUDIO IDAË, Rope Maps, Japan, Japan
properties.description_projet: The history of mapping shows that exploration of a territory allows to give a representation. Conversely, maps of the world helped the sailors to discover new territories. In “Rope maps”, ropes embody the link between nature, culture and technology. Used daily in the marine, sports or construction work, here it transforms itself into world maps. Using different sizes or colors, the ropes are tied, let down, stuck together to divert its use and create a dreamlike journey. Window display for 15 boutiques Hermès au Japon (Tokyo, Chiba, Nagoya, Kyoto, Urawa, Tamagawa)
properties.credits_photo: Nacása& Partners Inc./ Courtesy of Hermès Japon

properties.nom_etablissement: WY-TO, Head/home, Singapore, Singapore, Singapore
properties.description_projet: Husband-and-wife artist duo Alfredo and Isabel Aquilizan create works through the process of collecting and collaborating, using materials such as cardboard boxes and personal artefacts to illustrate the ideas of home, migration, family, and memory. As part of the Gallery Children’s Biennale 2021, the artists have created an immersive, large-scale phygital installation titled Head/Home. On-site, a collaborative workshop was conducted to involve children in the creation of small houses that contribute to the final installation, introducing the ideas of thinking and working with their hands. An online counterpart to the exhibit encourages children to continue the process of creating in their own homes. Children are invited to craft their own cardboard houses and submit them online to be featured in an ever-growing virtual floating city. These homes can also double up as wearable masks! In the Gallery of Self-Portraits, children may take a selfie with their creations and share their stories while discovering those of others. Through familiar landmarks and interactive workshops, the installation encourages children to be imaginative and express what their idea of home is.

properties.nom_etablissement: AW² | ARCHITECTURE & INTERIORS, Six Senses Crans-montana, Route des Téléphériques 60 3963, Crans-Montana, Valais, Suisse
properties.adresse: Route des Téléphériques 60 3963, Crans-Montana, Valais, Suisse
properties.description_projet: Situated in the heart of the Swiss Alps, the Six Senses Crans-Montana project is inscribed in the site as a powerful, tectonic structure. We studied the perception of the surrounding mountains, mirroring the natural environment to design a project that integrates into the landscape. The hotel accommodation and facilities are grouped together in the central 6-storey core structure which forms an elevated platform with two chalet-inspired residential buildings above. This platform provides panoramic views of the mountains from the bar, the outdoor swimming pool and lounge areas fitted out with log fires and a film projection station. The architecture and interiors of this alpine retreat have been designed to incite relaxation and revive the senses through an enveloping and cocooning experience in which the mountain views are given primary place. The project is based on the concept of dark to light, of gradually revealing what is hidden as a sensory architectural experience inspired by the surrounding environment. Like a rock emerging from the mountainside, the hotel extends outwards, reaching up towards the light. This concept has been applied to the journey that every guest embarks on from the moment they arrive at the underground entrance modelled on a mineral grotto. The building does not impose itself on the landscape but provides a framing of the environment through a play of perspectives and openings on to the exteriors. The interiors are based on a refined elegance using natural materials such as leather, wood and stone that reflect and dialogue with the surrounding nature. Six Senses Crans-Montana is a project balancing a strong aesthetic presence, respect for the environment and architecture that truly belongs in its site where the ‘ski-in and ski-out’ experience complements the extensive wellness spa. For the suites, we wanted to create a sense of ‘coming in from the cold’. The idea that the space is a cabin in the woods, a space to feel warm and safe, while in direct contact with surrounding nature. The rooms are thus lined in rough timber planks and stone-coloured wall render. The windows run the full width, with vast private balconies, taking in the views onto the ski slopes, forest and valley. The natural colour tones of the room were chosen to reinforce the idea of nature. The timber walls open with sliding panels into the bathroom space, which – as if carved into the mountain- is lined in stone. The suites we have designed expresses our idea of luxury at AW². It is understated, with every detail thought-out to create a connection to the context and environment. At the Six Senses Crans-Montana we were able to do so fully, by designing the space, the furniture, the lights and even some of the accessories. Six senses Crans-Montana’s indoor pool was thought-out as a mountain cave pool, while the details and materials are the same as the rest of the project. The stone lined walls and floors are juxtaposed to the sculptured ceiling in wood. The reflection of the timber ceiling battens – 15,000 of them – in the water creates a play of light with the sunlight filtering through the exterior courtyard lined in birch trees. This is a space that is suspended in time, where the seasons become part of the experience with the white snows in winter and the green leaves of the trees in summer. The spa is a major part of the project with over 2,000 square metres of space at the heart of the building. The treatment rooms, which we imagined as mountain cabins in the woods, are organised around the Alpine Garden, putting them in direct contact with nature outside. These timber-lined rooms contrast with the green of the trees outside. The wet treatment area offers a unique moment in multi sensorial experiences, all within the curved walled space. As if excavated directly into the mountain face.
properties.credits_photo: Mikael Bénard, Six Senses Hotels Resorts & Spas

properties.nom_etablissement: LUX, Birds, Copenhagen, Kongens Nytorv, Copenhague, Danemark
properties.description_projet: After 2 years of participation to the Copenhagen Light Festival, the duo Simon Chevalier & Lucile Cassassolles displays a new artwork in 2023, a way of creating a contemporary triptych for the festival with 4 original light sculptures. The installation has been commissioned by the City of Copenhagen and STROMMA (danish tourism office) and supported by Institut français du Danemark and the Creative Europe Programme of the European Union (implemented by Goethe Institut). This new temporary installation on public space, a work of light and scenography, was exhibited from 3 to 26 February 2023 on the main square of the city of Copenhagen, in front of the Embassy of France. LES OISEAUX is paying tribute to these small inhabitants, co-residents of our buildings, squares, and any architectural place. Echoing the year 2023 when the City of Copenhagen was elected 'World Capital of Architecture' by UNESCO and where many events were organized on this theme, we worked on an installation on an important theme in architecture: the implantation of nature in our urban planning. Across the country, birds face multiple threats but they also have to navigate our built environment, where they are especially challenged by light pollution and glass surfaces. These light sculptures represent the movement of a bird flight : 4 frames of a bird taking flight like a slow motion of the different phases of its flap. With superposing layers and illuminated parallel lines, the light installation creates an effect of « moiré » pattern, playing with our visual perception. With this artwork, the light artist Simon Chevalier wants to invite visitors to contemplation, imagination and introspection... and offer a suspended moment to enjoy and admire what surrounds us, the buildings and the architecture by being aware of all the living beings who enjoy the city with us. As part of this installation, we gave a masterclass at the Royal Academy of Design and Architecture in February 2023 on the theme of Art, Light and Architecture. (in partnership with the French Institute of Denmark).

properties.nom_etablissement: CHARLES ZANA, La Résidence, New York, New-York
properties.description_projet: A residence for culinary creation Charles Zana signed the opening of La Résidence in New York, the first physical outpost where Yann Nury's cuisine can be enjoyed in a private immersive environment. The project brings together these two enthusiasts to create a personal space of experimentation and conviviality. The loft, located in Soho New York on the 12th floor of an industrial building, has become a true creative laboratory for the chef. Designed as a living space for gastronomy, the professional kitchen opens onto a vast living room. All the furniture has been carefully chosen to fit perfectly into this new setting, echoing the history of the location and occupying the space that welcomes guests in a warm, contemporary mood. A vision of shared hospitality Yann Nury has taken up residence in a unique space designed by his friend Charles Zana, a regular visitor to New York City. Nury was eager to collaborate with Zana who he felt understood his vision most clearly. Together they were able to create an authentically unique gathering place. The loft incorporates both of their personalities and philosophies to create a simple but sophisticated place that highlights the balance between the chef's work on ingredients, textures and flavors and the architect's work on spaces, materials and atmospheres, all with a touch of modernity. Nury combines generosity with French-style traditions while Zana combines elegance with the enhancement of what exists. They wanted to create more than just an exceptional space or delicious food. Their approach is tinged with an unmistakable desire to create experiences. A symbiosis of the place’s architectural conception with the kitchen design To reveal the authenticity of the space, Charles Zana chose to recapture and enhance the essence of this light-filled loft by leaving the structure and technology visible, including the red and black industrial pipes that run the length of the ceiling. The original framework also revealed a magnificent skylight that was preserved. The harmony created by mixing the style of an American loft with the culture of French furniture gives the place its soul and makes it seem as if everything had been there for ages. At the center of the space, the kitchen is the first area clients discover when they arrive. Conceived as a stage on which the chef and his teams give a culinary performance, it has a Molteni gas stove surrounded by two huge work tables in gray Italian marble, made from raw Ceppo di Gré stone. Guests can sit on Pierre Jeanneret stools placed around these two “islands” to comfortably watch the cooks’ ballet from a front-row perspective. A daring culinary experience in a cultivated space Contemporary creations mingle with 20th century furniture from various sources, a symbol of the location’s eclecticism in the office adjoining the kitchen, one can see the Trama tapestry designed by Charles Zana, an armchair by Pierre Chapo and a selection of several pieces by Jean Touret made by the Ateliers de Marolles. Charles Zana selected a metal table designed for the Bank of France and manufactured by the Jansen workshops that takes its place in the dining room. Guests can also admire a Charlotte Perriand furniture unit reconstituted with 'diamond point' aluminum doors. At the back of the main room, the Guillaume sofa in dark green mohair designed by Charles Zana is the centerpiece of the lounge area. Its soft lines invite guests to a moment of conviviality and relaxation. Various major contemporary art works inhabit the space, including still lifes by Irving Penn and Robert Mapplethorpe as well as a Jean Dunand Art Deco gong that was once part of Andy Warhol's personal collection and a mushroom sculpture by Roxy Paine.

properties.nom_etablissement: PIERRE-YVES ROCHON, The Woodward Hotel, Geneva, Quai Wilson 37, 1201 Genève, Suisse
properties.description_projet: Nestled along the tranquil shores of Lake Geneva and surrounded by panoramic views of Mont Blanc, The Woodward has been masterfully renovated and reimagined. The post-Haussmann style limestone building, originally built in 1901 by French architect François Durel, has since been carefully transformed by PYR into a modern classical five-star urban retreat. Guests can appreciate a sense of Geneva’s spirit and heritage through the thoughtfully crafted interior experience that honors its history, culture, and natural landscape. The classical body of the hotel has been balanced with contemporary European furnishings, rich finishes, and an elegant palette of creams, blues, and greens that echo the soothing tones of the surrounding mountains and lake. The Woodward has been designed as more than just a hotel, as it is infused with the residential comfort of a “hôtel particulier”, or a private French mansion, where no corner has gone untouched and every space has been given distinct character with bespoke furnishings, hand-crafted design details, and rare art collections. It is designed as a spectacular home on the lake, with a mix of hand selected and personally curated items gathered throughout a life of travel. PYR's design was inspired by the history of the building by restoring the atmosphere of the time combining both authenticity through the use of noble materials such as ironwork, parquet, marble stone, and the generosity of the volumes and ceiling heights. As Geneva’s first all-suite hotel, guests can choose from luxurious and light-filled accommodations, while enjoying restaurants by Michelin-starred L’Atelier de Joël Robuchon, vegetable driven Le Jardinier by Alain Verzeroli, and Le Spa Guerlain at The Woodward. The Woodward Geneva features 26 suites.

properties.nom_etablissement: MAXIME D'ANGEAC ARCHITECTE, Orient Express Train, Paris – Istanbul, istanbul
properties.description_projet: LOOKING FOR A WORLD OF EXTREME LUXURY For this mythical train whose name raises only dreams and fantasies, it was not a question of copying and pasting the original Orient-Express, but rather to recreate the atmosphere of an exceptional train that would convey the same spirit, in a 21st century version. Inside the eighteen carriages, three of which have been transformed into suites, is an anthology of the finest French crafts. Woodwork, goldsmithing, marquetry... give life to an atmosphere over which hovers the poetry of a forgotten and rediscovered world, that of patience, observation, the time of exchanges, dressed dinners... For this mythical train, which was once decorated by René Prou, René Lalique, Christofle... and which will travel all over the world, Maxime d'Angeac has brought together the most beautiful materials, elm burr, mahogany, velvet, silk, beveled mirror, crystal... The rebirth of the Orient Express is a technological challenge, meeting scientific and technical criteria, and an artistic and aesthetic challenge where the entire project has been conceived as a total work of art. From the screws stamped Orient Express to the innovative concept of the suites, a few mind games and an exact science of detail will allow travelers to rediscover the great splendor of the Orient Express - says Maxime D'Angeac. A unique travel experience, imagined through a contemporary vision of comfort and extreme luxury. A real exercise in style to travel through the most beautiful landscapes of the world in a dreamlike and excellent way.

properties.nom_etablissement: TNT ARCHITECTURE, Elgringo, Seminyak, Kuta, Kabupaten de Badung, Bali, Indonésie
properties.adresse: Seminyak, Kuta, Kabupaten de Badung, Bali, Indonésie
properties.description_projet: A project of construction of two villas and pools designed, on a plot of land that was previously a rice field in the city. Taking advantage of the dimensional characteristics of the plot, the two constructions are settled at each ends of the plot ; the pools, designed in extension of each houses, assert the project in the linearity of the land. The architecture based on essential bioclimatic principles uses nature, orientation, and prevailing winds, to ensure ventilation and air conditioning for perfect cooled places. The volumes and plans allow good ventilation, and the design optimizes natural cooling, which is essential in the endemic tropical climate. To filter the sun radiations of exterior places, linear pergolas serve as both functional sunshades and decorative elements. Alongside the pools, contemporary peristyles with green planted roofs, protect the outisdes areas and provide pleasant spots of coolness and shade during the day. The villas were designed taking into account local construction know-how, with the use of locally sourced materials in a delicate, refined and welcoming writting.The woods are local teck, the masonry of the villas is made from local clay soil and adorned with coatings made from rice husks and clay. Today, urbanization has completely taken over the place, and the villas find themselves in the heart of the city. The architectural statements developped have permitted to anticipate those evolutions and the surroundings of each villas turned on themselves.

properties.description_projet: The vaulted neo-Gothic building has been restored to recapture its former architectural glory. Today, in what was once the ticket office of St Pancras station, eight-meter palm trees and chandeliers made from 267 hand-cut brass leaves preside over leather-clad tables and padded banquettes. In such a space, the challenge is to create intimacy - the bar, in antique brass, marble, and walnut, stretches 22 meters. Most of the furniture was custom-designed. "My primary ambition was to introduce a contemporary voice while staying connected to the past," explains Hugo Toro.

properties.nom_etablissement: Hauvette & Madani, IBIZA, Ibiza, Espagne
properties.description_projet: This project is a 150m penthouse located a stone's throw from the old town of EIvissa (Ibiza). The building, built in the 80's, enjoys a beautiful location but lacks the charm and soul of a traditional finca. charm and soul found in traditional Fincas. Together with the owner, Samantha & Lucas decided to create a décor that broke away from the original architecture of the place. with the original architecture of the place, bringing in more typical details and materials. The main material used is local microcemento. The architects brought in wooden beams and designed doors similar to those found in these old fincas. The idea: to give the place a family home feel, both simple and weathered. A A place that looks as if it has "always been there". The customer wanted a "chill" atmosphere, several places to hang out and entertain, from evening to (early) morning... (early) morning... "For the living room, we came up with an oversized masonry bench in the 70's style, which revolves around the living room, forming several "nooks". Around a large Indonesian wood coffee table. Indonesian wood. Nearby, a small reading nook, overlooked by a sconce by Guy Bareff (Galerie Desprez Brehet), has been created. To discover:Open kitchen, in varnished pine and microcemento, separated from the living room by a large bar (DCW pendant lights and Pols Potten stools). Dining room: vintage travertine table, chairs from Atelier Vime and Rock the Kasbah hanging lamp. Bedrooms and bathrooms: 3 bedrooms with en-suite bathrooms: microcemento and Bleu Provence fittings. Bedroom: vintage Audoux Minet sconces from Atelier Vime, Pols Potten bedside tables.

properties.nom_etablissement: MIAJA DESIGN GROUP, Lotte Hotel Busan, South Korea, 772 Gaya-daero, Busanjin-gu, Busan, South Korea
properties.description_projet: From the Three Kingdoms period to the present day, auspicious symbolisms from Korean history have represented people's aspirations for a better life. Bringing these symbolisms into our designs, we aim to bring a holistic and meaningful approach to the space we create. Seven Treasure Café and Pool Garden brings back the past by using traditional Korean motifs, seen as detailed visual art with symbolism, value, emotion and giving them a modern approach. Our aim was to create an oasis of peace and harmony, with Nature at the center of the concept linking the rooftop with its surrounding mountainous visuals. A design in full symbiosis with its past culture and rich history and magnificent natural environment.

properties.description_projet: A superb family resort, the recently renovated Club Med Sahoro Hokkaido is inspired by local Ainu culture and Japanese tradition. Touted as one of Asia's top travel destinations with idyllic views, Club Med Sahoro Hokkaido is the ideal resort to reconnect with loved ones and start new traditions among the snow-capped peaks of the Hidaka Mountains. Surrounded by the magnificent Hidaka mountain range, guests can experience the exclusivity of a private mountain on Mount Sahoro and marvel at the fine Japanese powder snow and magnificent scenery as they hurtle down the pristine slopes. Traditional Japanese culture is at the forefront of Club Med Sahoro Hokkaido's design philosophy, with a blend of authentic Ainu designs and the most modern amenities. The new look is reflected in the recently renovated rooms, which combine a nuanced level of modernity with traditional Japanese aesthetics, while preserving the beauty and splendor of Ainu culture.

properties.nom_etablissement: Sonia Rykiel Monaco
properties.adresse: Metropole Shopping, 17 Av. des Spélugues, 98000 Monaco
properties.description_projet:
Sonia Rykiel's resolutely graphic and colourful universe inhabits every nook and cranny of the space at Monaco's Metropole Shopping, taking visitors on a journey through the House's flagship inspirations. 
Metal, brushed steel and mesh have been introduced by the Uchronia studio to make the universe more contemporary and bring out the bright colours, particularly in the "Forever Room" dedicated to the House's accessible iconics. Between the bags are books, a tribute to Madame Rykiel's passion for literature. 
The collections presented in this showcase: Rykiel Forever, a new reinterpretation of the House's iconic knitwear, with its signature stripes and the legendary "Poor Boy sweater"; Velvet Strass, pieces combining the sparkle of rhinestones with the inimitable comfort of velvet; and Mai 68, the Autumn-Winter 2022 collection.

properties.adresse: Kayu-Manis JL. Monumen TNI AU Jl. Donoloyo No.8, Krobokan, Tamanan, Kec. Banguntapan, Kabupaten Bantul, Daerah Istimewa Yogyakarta 55191, Indonésie
properties.description_projet: The experience of this workshop in the Kayumanis Company in Yogjakarta, Indonesia, was rewarding in learning about another production model. When mass production in Europe became industrialized and largely automated, Kayumanis had about 115 workers in the workshops next to the design ofﬁce, which itself had a dozen people. The teak wood is worked mainly by hand and with the use of remote-controlled portable tools. The assemblies follow the rules of joinery, mortise and tenon joints, and are glued to meet the constraints of humidity since the furniture is exported to Europe mainly at the rate of one container per month. The major asset of this exchange for the company was to analyze the current trend in bathroom furniture in which they specialize. While teak wood is very solid, the bathroom trend in Europe is for lightness. Materials such as terrazzo used for basins are also highly appreciated and the "tropical" mood persists in decoration. I therefore chose to work teak in the form of strips, similar to the construction of boat decks. This results in a lighter effect than working with wood in its mass.

properties.nom_etablissement: Yaku
properties.description_projet: Yaku, a furniture collection in wood. 2017. I was selected by The French Institute to be artist in residence in Japan where I carried out research into the traditional art-form of Yaki-Sugi (burned wood). Following this experience, I created an outdoor furniture collection inspired by this ancient Japanese method and also by Sashimono art work. Traditionally used for making the kabuki theater objects, the technique consists of assembling wood pieces by jointing, using neither glue nor nails. The stools were made by M. Matsuda, a sashimono master based in Tokyo City.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon, Four Seasons Hotel Tianjin, 138 CHIFENG ROAD, 300041 HEPING DISTRICT, TIANJIN, CHINA
properties.adresse: 138 CHIFENG ROAD, 300041 HEPING DISTRICT, TIANJIN, CHINA
properties.description_projet: The Four Seasons Hotel Tianjin is an arrival to modern luxury on a grand scale, and a reflection of the culture and prosperity of a highly cosmopolitan urban destination. The design of the hotel is inspired by the richness of Tianjin’s heritage, the beauty of its surrounding landscapes, and internationally influenced design styles and details. A sense of monumental grandeur is conveyed immediately upon arrival to the hotel’s triple-height lobby on Level 2. The proportions and volumes of this open, airy space signal a departure from the busy pedestrian activity of surrounding streets and entry into a luxuriously elegant setting. Textures in wood and stone finishes echo the natural movements and colorations from regional landscapes and enhance the soothing, warm ambiance that ushers guests into the lobby. Four Seasons Hotel Tianjin features 215 guest rooms and 44 suites.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon, Grand Hotel Kronenhof, Via Maistra 130, 7504 Pontresina Switzerland  7504 Pontresina / St. Moritz · Schweiz
properties.adresse: Via Maistra 130, 7504 Pontresina Switzerland  7504 Pontresina / St. Moritz · Schweiz
properties.description_projet: The perfect synergy has been created between grand hotel style and Alpine living in Grand Hotel Kronenhof. Rooms convey a contemporary feel reflecting the local landscape and nature. Palette of beige and peach complements traditional Engadine homes in the region while green accents bring the colors of wooded slopes inside. The local vernacular is respected and combined with international expectations blending to create luxurious and tranquil spaces. Grand Hotel Kronenhof features 112 guest rooms and suites.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon, The Woodward Hotel, Quai Wilson 37, 1201 Geneva Switzerland
properties.description_projet: Nestled along the tranquil shores of Lake Geneva and surrounded by panoramic views of Mont Blanc, The Woodward has been masterfully renovated and reimagined. The post-Haussmann style limestone building, originally built in 1901 by French architect François Durel, has since been carefully transformed by PYR into a modern classical five-star urban retreat. Guests can appreciate a sense of Geneva’s spirit and heritage through the thoughtfully crafted interior experience that honors its history, culture, and natural landscape. The classical body of the hotel has been balanced with contemporary European furnishings, rich finishes, and an elegant palette of creams, blues, and greens that echo the soothing tones of the surrounding mountains and lake. The Woodward has been designed as more than just a hotel, as it is infused with the residential comfort of a “hôtel particulier”, or a private French mansion, where no corner has gone untouched and every space has been given distinct character with bespoke furnishings, hand-crafted design details, and rare art collections. It is designed as a spectacular home on the lake, with a mix of hand selected and personally curated items gathered throughout a life of travel. As Geneva’s first all-suite hotel, guests can choose from luxurious and light-filled accommodations, while enjoying restaurants by Michelin-starred L’Atelier de Joël Robuchon, vegetable driven Le Jardinier by Alain Verzeroli, and Le Spa Guerlain at The Woodward. The Woodward Geneva features 26 suites.

properties.nom_etablissement: Grégoire Maisondieu, Restaurant Black Papper, Avenue de la gare, Meknès, Maroc
properties.adresse: Avenue de la gare, Meknès, Maroc
properties.description_projet: Black Pepper is a restaurant located in the city of Meknes (Morocco). The astonishing Moroccan sunlight, filters through a dense network of louvers revealing the double height space and its materials. A mezzanine space, part of the public area, overhangs the main space, and announces the kitchen, behind a set of portholes. Downstairs, bar and show kitchen are open on the space. Raw materials such as burned wood, brick, concrete, are the components of the envelope of the place. Leather, wood (cedar from a local forest), marble (black marble with white veins from a local quarry), are the components of the finishes of the furniture, bringing precision and refinement to the project. Green plants in huge terra cotta jars punctuate the space, bringing sweetness and freshness to it.

properties.nom_etablissement: Grégoire Maisondieu, Villa R, Rabat, Maroc
properties.description_projet: This is the main residence of a couple and their two children. The house is developed on three levels: Ground floor: reception, living areas First floor: four beedrooms (family and guests). Basement: level of leisure (gym, spa and cinema room) and services. They wanted a house that would allow them to make the most of the climate of Rabat, an oceanic climate that allows you to be outdoors most of the year. A house with spaces where the family can meet, but where everyone can also have their privacy. An easy to live house, located in a new district of the Moroccan capital. Everything in the project has been done to erase the borders between interior and exterior, and on the contrary bring continuity and fluidity to the spaces, while avoiding a monumental aspect. Some examples: Interior / exterior continuity of the stone cladding of the walls on the ground floor and the basement. These walls are dressed in Tetouan Stone, a moroccan stone of grey color, quite textured and lively. (Tetouan is a city from the north mediterranean part of Morocco). For instance, you can notice the large supporting wall extending over more than 35m from the swimming pool to the revisited Moroccan living room, punctuated by the fountain, the fireplace and some contemporary artworks. Visual continuity of the ceiling between interior and exterior. In the dining room the ribbed pattern in wooden slats extends outside without interruption. The swimming pool slips under the covered terrace, as close as possible to the living-room. The terrace decks runs alongside the pool and extends inside where it delimits the dining area. These different details mean that as soon as the large bay window (12 linear meters) is opened, we no longer know where the border is between the inside and the outside. From the outside, in distant view, the mineral base (Tetouan stone) is perceived as a plinth on which is placed the level of the bedrooms, imagined as an extruded box coated with white. From the garden, you can see that large roof overhangs have been provided for protection from the sun. Upstairs, from the south, the three family bedrooms communicate by a deep covered balcony. A system of retractable louvers allows you to adjust the degree of privacy and protection from the sun. In the basement, the service areas and those linked to leisure activities (sports hall, spa and cinema room) take their natural light by vegetated courtyards.

properties.adresse: Place Vendôme Mall Lusail Faubourg - Gate 5, Doha, Qatar
properties.description_projet:
To inaugurate the new Hermès'store in Doha, Qatar, Hermès wished to highlight Alexis Tricoire's universe, committed to sustainable development. His proposal was to create an unexpected 2000m2 organic shape architecture with a succession of woven bamboo caves. He brought life with his biomimetic creations based on recycled industrial materials, in continuity with his previous works made in iconic places. This setup, in front of the Persic Golf, gave the opportunity to Tricoire Design studio to share again his message beyond the europeens borders about the significance of recycling for nature's preservation. Guest were invited for a tremandous experience in this poetic setup enhanced by the talented light designer David Debrinay and the famous sound designer Alain Français.

Each alcove of this surprising architecture accommodates an artistic installation based on recycled brushes. The journey starts under the orange light tree then invites us to pass under the up side down garden with his two giant anacondas facing three dancing birds flying over the hills landscape. In a second time we discover the Dome's constellation made of a recycled brushed. The main stage hosting the artists is framed by amazing fountains in sprays of metal shimmering blue.Then we turn over a cloudy landscape where we can observe a monkey, peacefully sited on the land. The journey continues in a vault inhabited by luminous headdresses which leads us outside to a flock of mocking birds. From the terrace facing the sea, behind the bamboo hills appears Doha'skyline.

properties.nom_etablissement: Lina Ghotmeh—Architecture, Sara Hildén Art Museum
properties.annee_projet: Design Competition
properties.description_projet:
Acting as a “city within the city” the Finlayson factory hosted a multiplicity of programs that gathered a strong community around them. Enlivening the spirit of the place and its genius loci, as well as pursuing an open dialogue into the future, Sara Hilden’s Art New Museum whispers in conversation with its surroundings. It dialogues with the history of the place to derive its own iconic and distinctive architectural identity. This project aims to offer to Sara Hildén Foundation both a functional and flexible tool to host the collection as well as a symbol of an environmentally just and frugal architecture. Efficiently built with brick and wood, both locally produced structural materials, the museum is the opportunity for the city of Tampere to unfold and recompose its industrial past into a novel future. 

Here this contemporary factory-like, house of Arts becomes a “knitting platform”. While its patterned deep red brick fa-cade sparkle in glaze, literally drawing their aesthetics from the textile patterns formerly produced by the many women working in Finlayson, the building itself represents a public platform able to “knit” its site. Moving from the generous heights of its transparent ground level — linking Finlayson palace to Tehtaan pääkonttori — into its rather iconic womb like roof, the building assembles and re-links the social, the architecture and the urban fabric. While invited to gaze at the extent of Tampere, its lakes, the extent of forest from the heights of the last floor terrace, one cannot but hear the poetic chants intertwining the built and the natural heritage into a human scale.

The focus on earth tones is heavily inspired by colors present on wooded slopes in the local environment. Dark wood paneling, recessed windows, and deep green drapes transport guests to another century. Kronenhof Smokers’ Lounge features 20 seats.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon Le Cap Hong Kong83 Lai Ping Rd, Kau To Shan, Hong Kong
properties.adresse: 83 Lai Ping Rd, Kau To Shan, Hong Kong
properties.description_projet: Nestled at the peak of Kau to Shan, an unmatched panorama greets the residents of Le Cap, a newly constructed luxury residential development with houses, apartments and a clubhouse surrounded by cypress trees, bougainvillea and lavender. With views of Hong Kong’s sparkling blue sea and verdant green hills, this retreat takes its name from the sun-kissed beauty of SaintJean-Cap-Ferrat in the French Riviera. Exteriors are inspired by lush Mediterranean gardens and interiors are detailed with the timeless elegance of the 1930’s, altogether bridging the classic Art Deco period with contemporary modernism in this true urban retreat. Le Cap Residences features 29 houses and 40 apartments.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon Les Caves de Taillevent BeirutLes Caves de Taillevent, Les Jardins de Tabaris, Beirut, Lebanon

properties.description_projet: Following success in the French capital, Les Caves de Taillevent opened another location in Beirut as one of the most important showcases for French viticulture. It is a concept store dedicated to wine; a combination of a wine boutique with 1,600 offerings, an intimate bar, and wine academy featuring a series of classes and seminars focusing on wine, winemaking, and wine appreciation. The unique selections come from the most famous appellations to the most discreet; over an area of 500 sqm, 6,000 bottles span across three floors, offering original, uniquely found bottles scouted from vineyards all over the world. Les Caves de Taillevent features 30 seats.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon L'Osier by Shiseido Tokyo 7-5-5 Ginza, Chuo-ku, Tokyo 104-0061
properties.description_projet: The newest incarnation of Shiseido’s famous three-star French restaurant, L’Osier, is a masterful composition in warm whites and gold. Elegant white linens and chairs, pale yellow banquettes, and camellia-patterned gold carpets diffuse luminosity. The essence of the Shiseido brand evokes elegance, transparency, and luxury. The atmosphere is created through the perfect balance between Neo-Impressionism, Art Deco and Japonism; developed in tandem with the history of Ginza and serving as a bridge between the cities of Tokyo and Paris. L’Osier by Shiseido features 46 seats.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon The St. Regis RomeVia Vittorio Emanuele Orlando, 3, 00185 Roma RM, Italy
properties.adresse: Via Vittorio Emanuele Orlando, 3, 00185 Roma RM, Italy
properties.description_projet: The full-scale restoration for The St. Regis Rome includes all areas for socializing and entertaining such as the lobby, and library, as well as all of the hotel’s guest rooms and opulent suites. Elegantly layered pastel hues breathe new life into the guest rooms, while a regal palette of black and gold anchors the lobby, which is punctuated by intricate moldings, arched entry ways and fluted columns, with an abundance of natural light falling upon the cream, white and dove grey tones of the space. Materials used in the restoration, such as travertine and bronze, reference the Italian capital’s architectural heritage and traditions of fine artisanship. Magnificent sculptural busts, mosaics and objets d’art are displayed alongside plush fabrics. Aristocratic Roman patterns are further enriched by touches of deep yellow, powder blue, and noble shimmers of gold and silver. The St. Regis Rome features 138 guest rooms and 28 suites.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon The Peninsula ShanghaiThe Peninsula Shanghai, No. 32 The Bund 32 Zhongshan Dong Yi Road Shanghai 200002 The People'S Republic Of China
properties.adresse: The Peninsula Shanghai, No. 32 The Bund 32 Zhongshan Dong Yi Road Shanghai 200002 The People'S Republic Of China
properties.description_projet: The Peninsula Shanghai interiors are a modern interpretation of the glamorous era of “The Paris of the East” – Shanghai in the 1920s and 1930s. The interiors mix materials and motifs from the Art Deco period and traditional Chinese elements, incorporating state-of-the-art technology and signature Peninsula accents. The guest rooms and suites have two distinct color palettes – celadon or cerulean blue and ivory. The rooms incorporate traditional materials used in Shanghai in the 1920s in the furniture and millwork, including mahogany and ebony woods, black St Laurent and off-white St Talino marble, black lacquer, carved glass and polished chrome. Traditional Chinese accents include hand-painted panels and fabrics. The cream marble bathrooms are accented with black and chrome details, carved opaque glass panels in the double vanities, and an intricate stylized floral hand-carved panel over the bathtub. The public areas use the celadon palette, creating continuity with the guest rooms. The dramatic and elegant double-height lobby is given definition with limestone columns and balconies from the first floor ballroom and meeting areas. The black marble floor and limestone walls are enhanced with a backlit carved-glass ceiling, spectacular chandeliers and murals running the height of the lobby. The eclectic bars and restaurants pay homage to Shanghai’s place as a center of style and commerce in the 30s, using nautical, aviation, and traditional Chinese residences as signature elements.The Peninsula Shanghai features 191 guest rooms and 44 suites.

properties.nom_etablissement: Pierre-Yves Rochon Jade Signature Miami16901 Collins Ave Suite 2805, Sunny Isles Beach, FL 33160, United States
properties.adresse: 16901 Collins Ave Suite 2805, Sunny Isles Beach, FL 33160, United States
properties.description_projet: Rising 57 stories above Sunny Isles Beach and the sparkling blue Atlantic Ocean, PYR translates the strikingly modern architectural form of the newly constructed Jade Signature tower into a warm and welcoming interior residential experience. Colorations inspired by the sun, sand, ocean and lush greenery accent a clean white palette throughout three full floors of amenity spaces, including lounges, swimming pools, beach bar, fitness center and a full-service Tata Harper spa. Curved lines and soaring volumes celebrate the building architecture and the spirit of Miami, while intimate alcoves, midcentury modern furnishings and rich materials infuse the building with warmth and comfort.

Taking advantage of its strategic location, the Crystal Tower is elegantly prismatic shape with offset games - plastic, structural, environmental - resulting in urban and programmatic data. Buoyed by the rationalism of the formal structure and plastic architecture, the project is also based on the importance of the story. Born to a geographic context and a specification that it has complied, we chose to baptize Cristal Tower, which it is important not to underestimate the power of evocation: it is from this word, both symbolic identifiable appropriated, unifying, that will be born a story around which the various parties can be stored without affecting the overall coherence.

properties.description_projet: Franklin Azzi Design, in collaboration with fashion designer Serge Ruffieux, has designed and developed an exclusive collection of furniture around the MINIMAL/MAXIMAL concept for the Chinese ready-to-wear brand EP YAYING. The raw beauty of the materials, such as jade and concrete, combines with the elegance of lacquer work and embroidery. Between the association of rough and smooth surfaces, matte and gloss colors, the traditional mixing of materials of Chinese craftsmanship, the boutiques reveal their singularity in a play of contrasts between stark simplicity and maximalism. Artistic collaboration: Serge Ruffieux, fashion designer

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture EP YAYING SHANGHAIShanghai Yaheng Fashion Co, Ltd N. 6 9, Lane 890 Hengshan Road Hengshanfang Shanghai China
properties.adresse: Shanghai Yaheng Fashion Co, Ltd N. 6 9, Lane 890 Hengshan Road Hengshanfang Shanghai China
properties.description_projet: The Chinese brand EP YAYING called on Franklin Azzi to design the new architectural concept of Shanghai, Jiaxing, New York's flagships, and an architectural bible to deploy the brand in 300 international stores. Reflecting the approach of the iconic label in the revival of luxury goods and Chinese heritage – the name EP YAYING means ‘pledge of quality’ – Franklin Azzi drew from Oriental cultural references and know-hows to design a minimal/maximal concept. This approach resulted in a program of spaces dedicated to experimentation and strolling, cultivating oxymoron in every detail, and evolving uniquely with each new store. The architecture of the boutiques - in both new and existing buildings - focuses on transparency, openness to the outdoors and integration of nature. The space dedicated to the brand joins the public space in a principle of fluid urbanity. The raw beauty of the materials, such as jade and concrete, is combined with the elegance of lacquer work and embroidery. The boutiques reveal their singularity in a play of contrasts between stark simplicity and maximalism, between the association of rough and smooth surfaces, matte and gloss colors and the traditional mixing of materials of Chinese craftsmanship. From floor to ceiling, through the furniture and changing rooms designed as transition and exhibition spaces in dialogue with the overall scheme, an unusual journey was designed, composed of aesthetic and sensorial resonances. A means for the architect to bring modernity and craftsmanship into dialogue in an original approach that sees each new EP YAYING boutique as a unique venue. Artistic collaboration: Serge Ruffieux, fashion designer Awards: Architizer A+ Awards 2022, finalist in the Retail category Dezeen Awards 2022, longlisted in the Large Interior Retail category Frame Awards 2022, nominee

The wood details work, and the assembly of the armchair and bench required close cooperation between Franklin Azzi Design and a local cabinetmaker.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Isabel Marant Beirut2 Park Avenue Mina El Hosn Beirut Central District Beyrouth Lebanon
properties.adresse: 2 Park Avenue Mina El Hosn Beirut Central District Beyrouth Lebanon
properties.description_projet: Located at the Palladium 2 on Park Avenue Mina El Hosn, Isabel Marant Beirut store is on two floors, a ground floor and a basement. The ground floor area – covered with a ceiling made of thin solid oak slats that filter light – has a large wall covered with grey mirrors, floor and walls made of glossy light grey waxed concrete, and specific furniture. A large cash desk and a bench welcome clients. A large platform dedicated to window display also allows exhibitions of artists’ sculptures and installations. The basement floor hosts a second retail space as well as large fitting rooms and a jewelry area. Fitting rooms are entirely covered of light felt, with low pieces of furniture. Each fitting room is embedded with a solid oak bench, a large bright mirror and matt black steel rack. Special attention was given to the design of specific furniture, especially the cash desk and the two benches. All furniture is in solid oak, while the cushions and seatings are in natural leather, with saddle stitch.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Isabel Marant Dubaï Mall of Emirate, 2nd Floor Dubaï United Arab Emirates
properties.adresse: Mall of Emirate, 2nd Floor Dubaï United Arab Emirates
properties.description_projet: The Isabel Marant boutiques created by the agency are part of a process of creation and permanent architectural research. Thus, each boutique is a unique piece rooted in the place and culture of the country in which it is located. The new Isabel Marant boutique in Dubai, located in the Mall of the Emirates - Fashion Dome - is a unique space. It is long and has two entrances and two windows facing each other. Based on these spatial characteristics, the interior design is conceived as a free plan, freeing the central space from any clutter. This clear structure gives the store a coherent whole and a fluidity of apprehension of the spaces. The impression that emerges is a composition of different perpendicular planes assembled in three dimensions: the floor, the ceiling, the walls and the furniture. Vertically, the mineral walls, slightly detached from the existing envelope, offer surfaces for the staging of clothing. Others, arranged freely in the space like an abstract sculpture, partition and delimit the spaces: windows, fitting rooms, point of sale, Isabel Marant and Etoile space. Made of travertine, they are implemented in the image of a wood marquetry, creating subtle geometric combinations with the different directions of veining of the stone. The choice of rich natural materials, such as travertine, wood, vegetable leather, and precious metals such as brass offer, in an ordered geometry, a minimal and luxurious setting to the new Isabel Marant store.

properties.description_projet: The functional conception, the aesthetical approach and the choice of fabric of Côte & Ciel calls to an aware clientele, as well as to the sanctimonious people of the fashion world. From the streetwear bag to the Ipad pouch, all the fabric of Côte & Ciel are made from ecological textile thread, a fabric made possible with the help of an ecological dying technician. Created in 2008 and based in Paris, the brand Côte & Ciel has asked our agency to develop a concept for its future stores – an architectural chart. The first corner was implanted in New York, at 355A Bowery Street, near Lower East Side of Manhattan, one of the neighbourhoods harbouring many high class stores nowadays and always evolving.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi ArchitectureFrench Pavilion for Dubai 2020 World's FairDubai
properties.titre_affiche: French Pavilion for Dubai 2020 World's Fair
properties.description_projet: A desert, water and light architecture. “I have always loved the desert. One sits down on a desert sand dune, sees nothing, hears nothing. Yet through the silence something throbs, and gleams...” Antoine de Saint-Exupéry. Anchoring, digging, drawing, revealing the spirit of the places. As it could be the leitmotiv that led us through the 2020 French Pavillon conception in Dubai. This town from the Arabian Gulf carries within itself the fascinating imagination of the Arabian architecture based on the art of geometry and poetics of light. Thanks to its location, it is also a land with extreme climate conditions and a peculiar geological composition. As part of World’s Fair, beyond demonstrating our ability to conceive and build, the stake has an influence even more symbolic. The architecture proposed needs to represent with respect and intelligence the link between our two countries, France and the United Arab Emirates. Our ambitions are: to show French excellence in various fields (industry, sciences, education, culture…) with pride, to create a bridge between Western and Eastern cultures, and then to offer a message with a worldwide resonance. Indeed, this is the mission of the World’s Fair: being the world’s center of ideas, innovation and creation during 6 months of event.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Dubaï Hotel, Mama ShelterAl Khaleej Al Tejari 2 St DUBAI United Arab Emirates
properties.adresse: Al Khaleej Al Tejari 2 St DUBAI United Arab Emirates
properties.description_projet: Mama Shelter, the global collection of authentic hotels, has announced plans to open a new location in Dubai. The property will be located in Dubai’s downtown Business Bay and is expected to open in 2020. Designed by Franklin Azzi Architecture, Mama Shelter Dubai will have 201 rooms and 80 residences. The architect explained: “Mama will offer a unique tower to Dubai. A pure glass coat covering a wooden skin made by each rooms’ shutters.” The rooms are sanctuaries with the comforts of home coupled with all the needs of digital modernity, with spacious king size beds and high speed wi-fi. With 300-sq-m of space set aside for collaboration, travellers will have room to gather, create or simply hang out. The property will feature a mix of modern hotel rooms, with one bedroom and two bedroom residences offering cutting-edge design elements specially crafted by famed interior designer Thierry Gaugain. Guests will be able to unwind at an all-day dining restaurant, trendy rooftop bar, lobby bar, café, volleyball court, basketball court and swimming pool. “We knew Dubai was the perfect destination for our eighth Mama Shelter property because the city embodies the Mama spirit with its bustling excitement and international appeal,” said Mama Shelter Founder, Serge Trigano. “Mama Shelter Dubai will not just be a place for business meetings and flythroughs, but a place to live, work, laugh, debate, celebrate, and at the end of the night, come home to Mama." Bader Mohamed Yousuf Bukhamas, chairman of Khamas Group of Investment Companies, said: “We are delighted to partner with an international operator such as AccorHotels for the launch of its iconic lifestyle brand Mama Shelter in the Middle East.” Mama Shelter will also benefit from its proximity to landmarks such as the Downtown Dubai area, the Burj Khalifa and Dubai Mall. Alongside the concentration of lifestyle hospitality projects across Business Bay, Mama Shelter will be positioned as an iconic destination with the presence of an additional five-star hotel within the same tower. Pawan Kachroo, managing director of Khamas Hospitality said: “This project is reflective of a shared vision to bring desired diversity and delight in the regional hospitality industry with fresh innovation. Through the Mama Shelter Dubai Business Bay, we intend to energize the industry with competitive experience driven offerings.” The Trigano Family, co-founders of Club Med, created Mama Shelter eight years ago with an inaugural location in Paris. Since then the family has expanded Mama Shelter all over the world in Marseille, Lyon, Bordeaux, Los Angeles and Rio de Janeiro. In February, the company announced plans to open Mama Shelter Prague in early 2018.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Isabel Marant L.A8454 Melrose Place, Los Angeles, CA 90069, États-Unis
properties.adresse: 8454 Melrose Place, Los Angeles, CA 90069, États-Unis
properties.description_projet: Isabel Marant decided to call on the office once more to design the new Los Angeles store in the popular WEHO (West Hollywood) district. The gardens surrounding the property are filled with statues made by the French artist Arnold Goron, giving another French touch to the place. The store is on a single level including a 150 square meter retail space with a 200 square meter private garden. The garden’s floral display is based on a green-color chromatic study that visually creates a circular motion, going from dark to light green. The lighter shades of the vegetation coincide with the sunniest parts of the garden. The main part of the store is flooded with natural light thanks to the large, glazed façade and roof. The space consists of two large solid oak wardrobes that adorn the walls and showcase Isabel Marant creations. Moreover, these wardrobes can open and close whenever, according to the needs and desires. While the second room is a dedicated space for the ‘Star’ collection with spacious dressing rooms and jewelry counter. The architecture of this project exudes a particular intimacy, similar to that of a house, far from the usual store conventions.

Today, Jerome Dreyfuss bags are sold in over 300 outlets in the world such as Liberty, Harrods and Matches in London, Barneys and Saks in New York and LA, Maria Luisa in Shanghai, Isetan in Tokyo and Printemps, Galeries Lafayette and Le Bon Marché in Paris ... In addition, the house has three stores at Paris (two for women, one for men), a flagship store in New York, 11 corners and a flagship store in South Korea, where it continues to develop its reputation. In ten years, Jerome Dreyfuss has sit reputation. Although her bags have found their way to the arms of the most elegant women of the moment such as Julianne Moore, Keira Knightley, Sarah Jessica Parker, Diane Kruger and Jessica Biel, the real satisfaction Jerome rest of his creations cross the streets.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Sasaek - Horizons175, Jingwan-dong, Eunpyeong-gu, Seoul Korea (South)
properties.description_projet: The French architect Franklin Azzi is the 3rd place winner of the International Competition for National Museum of Korean Literature in Seoul. Sasaek is imagined as a welcoming, flexible and harmonious place, unified with the vegetation, the rock, water and mountains. It is a ‘continuum’, a bridge between time and space, nature and literature. The National Museum of Korean Literature is inviting the visitors on a voyage through the garden of four seasons and shared ideas. Its planted roof forms a footbridge on a hiking trail, linking mountainside and valley. Tucked into the slope of the mountain and reflected in the mirror of water at the centre of its internal courtyard, the museum melts into a site propitious to strolling, contemplation and reflection. Our ambition is to create a museum ‘capable’ of ensuring its primary roles (collecting, conserving, restoring) and to fulfill its vocation of relating the individual to the collective while contributing to the enhancement of a shared heritage and knowledge for all. Sasaek works as a museum–footbridge, at one with literature, history, architecture and nature. Franklin Azzi Architecture - Retmus architects, consultant & local partner Architizer A+ Awards 2022, winner for the Unbuilt Cultural category

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Bali Barret - Red Bunker 01148 Shibuya-ku, 1500002 Tokyo, Japon
properties.description_projet: The “red bunker” offers a brutalist face to the Shibuya neighbourhood, in Tokyo. Contrasting with the light and delicate Japanese buildings around it, the project detaches from its context and introduces a new concept of architectural graft with an archetype of military construction. Differing from its surroundings by the absence of a front window display, this UFO takes its inspiration from the tight volumes of military bunkers, with thick slanted walls, gun ports and baffles inside. For this project, the issue is addressed in reverse: the red concrete façade acts as a city-wide landmark that can be seen from afar. The point is to catch the eye of the passersby with this unexpected formalism in the heart of Tokyo: the opacity of the façade gives off so little information on the building that it arouses people’s curiosity.

properties.nom_etablissement: Franklin Azzi Architecture Bali Barret - Red Military Tent 025115 Jungumae 1500002 Tokyo Japan
properties.description_projet: Since 2003, Mrs. Bali Barret is part of the French Haute Couture House Hermès, where she took over as the new creative director for women's universe of silk and textile. Prior to that, she created her own brand: Bali Barret. The ‘Red Military Tent’ accommodates her second store, hidden behind a large tarpaulin. In addition to being unusual, this project appeals for its manufacturing process – a breakthrough from the traditional store design codes. To comply with the function it houses, this architecture uses an appropriate design language – that of textile creation. In the same way as a seamstress would reconstruct a piece of clothing from a pattern, the contractors were provided with a facade pattern of the tent. The waxed canvas is tensioned with natural leather straps and spanned on a metal framework. The base is weighted down with sandbags. To enter the tent, you walk through a timber entrance lobby and then discover an interior space with ecru walls. Both the opacity of the facade and the lack of information of this unexpected formalism are a way to attract the curious of Downtown Tokyo. It is the purpose that the project was intended to serve – for six years, the store had become a new urban landmark.
